49
00:06:03,299 --> 00:06:07,298
At age 25, Adolf Hitler is a poor loner,

50
00:06:07,299 --> 00:06:10,298
an aspiring artist,

51
00:06:10,299 --> 00:06:12,799
struggling to survive.

52
00:06:14,299 --> 00:06:16,298
Both his parents are dead...

53
00:06:16,299 --> 00:06:19,299
[Thunder booming]

54
00:06:19,300 --> 00:06:22,676
Leaving Hitler truly alone in the world.

55
00:06:24,299 --> 00:06:25,633
He was a lost soul.

56
00:06:25,634 --> 00:06:28,298
He wanted to be an artist,

57
00:06:28,299 --> 00:06:32,175
but he couldn't get into the art school,

58
00:06:32,176 --> 00:06:34,967
and he ended up living in a flophouse.

59
00:06:41,299 --> 00:06:44,800
Narrator: Left without
any means of support,

60
00:06:44,801 --> 00:06:48,633
his only way to make money is
selling paintings around town

61
00:06:48,634 --> 00:06:51,298
for next to nothing.

62
00:06:51,299 --> 00:06:54,298
Hitler didn't have a plan
B when he was rejected.

63
00:06:54,299 --> 00:06:55,794
He just didn't know what to do.

64
00:06:55,795 --> 00:06:59,298
So he started to drift.

65
00:06:59,299 --> 00:07:00,930
He had very little money.

66
00:07:00,931 --> 00:07:03,298
He was living in a hand-to-mouth existence.

67
00:07:03,299 --> 00:07:05,466
He had no clear aim in life at all.

68
00:07:05,467 --> 00:07:08,799
He was, in a sense, waiting
for something to happen.

69
00:07:10,467 --> 00:07:12,298
Narrator: Before long,

70
00:07:12,299 --> 00:07:16,298
a chance event 450 miles away

71
00:07:16,299 --> 00:07:19,799
will change everything.

72
00:07:22,299 --> 00:07:25,298
June 28, 1914.

73
00:07:25,299 --> 00:07:26,633
[Explosion]

74
00:07:26,634 --> 00:07:31,347
An assassin takes down the
Archduke of Austria-Hungary.

75
00:07:33,299 --> 00:07:37,298
The murder ignites a deadly conflict

76
00:07:37,299 --> 00:07:39,799
that quickly erupts into war.

77
00:07:41,299 --> 00:07:43,298
From the tangle of alliances

78
00:07:43,299 --> 00:07:45,298
two sides emerge.

79
00:07:45,299 --> 00:07:47,298
Britain, France, and Russia

80
00:07:47,299 --> 00:07:50,298
become known as the Allies,

81
00:07:50,299 --> 00:07:54,298
while Austria-Hungary,
Germany, and the Ottoman Empire

82
00:07:54,299 --> 00:07:56,676
form the Central Powers.

83
00:07:58,299 --> 00:08:01,298
Filled with a patriotic sense of urgency,

84
00:08:01,299 --> 00:08:05,299
men on both sides rush to join the fight.

85
00:08:05,300 --> 00:08:09,298
For Hitler, it's the opportunity
he's been waiting for.

86
00:08:09,299 --> 00:08:12,299
He quickly rushes to enlist.

87
00:08:12,300 --> 00:08:14,298
He tried out for the Austrian army.

88
00:08:14,299 --> 00:08:16,298
He failed the physical.

89
00:08:16,299 --> 00:08:19,298
He wasn't considered strong
enough to carry a rifle.

90
00:08:19,299 --> 00:08:22,298
Narrator: Rejected by his own country,

91
00:08:22,299 --> 00:08:24,466
Hitler turns to the German army

92
00:08:24,467 --> 00:08:27,298
who's accepting almost anyone

93
00:08:27,299 --> 00:08:31,298
as they worked to build
the largest fighting force

94
00:08:31,299 --> 00:08:33,799
in the world.

95
00:08:37,299 --> 00:08:40,799
[Bells tolling]

96
00:08:45,299 --> 00:08:47,466
Germany has finally given Hitler

97
00:08:47,467 --> 00:08:51,298
what he's always wanted:

98
00:08:51,299 --> 00:08:52,800
A place to belong.

99
00:08:54,378 --> 00:08:56,298
I think that the decision
to enter the military

100
00:08:56,299 --> 00:08:59,298
for most people is not a decision to serve.

101
00:08:59,299 --> 00:09:01,298
It may be in a very general sense,

102
00:09:01,299 --> 00:09:03,008
but it's more often

103
00:09:03,009 --> 00:09:05,799
because something else is motivating you.

104
00:09:12,299 --> 00:09:14,799
<i>Zwei!</i>

105
00:09:16,634 --> 00:09:18,799
<i>Drei!</i>

106
00:09:20,299 --> 00:09:21,799
<i>Vier!</i>

107
00:09:23,299 --> 00:09:25,466
Narrator: Throughout August of 1914,

108
00:09:25,467 --> 00:09:28,799
Hitler trains as a
Private in the German army.

109
00:09:29,818 --> 00:09:31,298
Well, the German army was considered

110
00:09:31,299 --> 00:09:34,298
to be the finest army in the world.

111
00:09:34,299 --> 00:09:36,299
It was a massive force...

112
00:09:36,300 --> 00:09:39,298
well equipped, well trained,

113
00:09:39,299 --> 00:09:40,298
and very well led,

114
00:09:40,299 --> 00:09:44,298
and Hitler was swept away.

115
00:09:44,299 --> 00:09:45,800
Being part of the German army

116
00:09:45,801 --> 00:09:49,799
was something that Hitler deeply loved.

117
00:09:54,299 --> 00:09:57,298
Narrator: The structure of
training transforms Hitler

118
00:09:57,299 --> 00:09:59,800
into a devout German soldier.

119
00:10:02,299 --> 00:10:05,298
Hitler joins 1 1/2 million Germans

120
00:10:05,299 --> 00:10:07,298
marching towards the French border

121
00:10:07,299 --> 00:10:10,298
and the unified Allied forces.

122
00:10:10,299 --> 00:10:12,800
In the history of warfare,

123
00:10:12,801 --> 00:10:16,799
armies this large have never met in combat.

124
00:10:18,299 --> 00:10:21,298
6,000 miles away,

125
00:10:21,299 --> 00:10:23,799
America has nothing to
do with the war in Europe.

126
00:10:25,299 --> 00:10:27,298
They're in their own war

127
00:10:27,299 --> 00:10:29,298
with Pancho Villa.

128
00:10:29,299 --> 00:10:32,175
[Hooves rumbling]

129
00:10:32,176 --> 00:10:34,298
[Gunshots]

130
00:10:34,299 --> 00:10:36,298
The Mexican Revolutionary

131
00:10:36,299 --> 00:10:39,298
is carrying out violent
attacks on U.S. citizens

132
00:10:39,299 --> 00:10:41,799
along the southwestern border.

133
00:10:45,300 --> 00:10:47,799
But he goes too far.

134
00:10:58,299 --> 00:11:01,799
[Gunshots ricocheting]

135
00:11:04,300 --> 00:11:08,008
Villa and his men seize
an American mining train,

136
00:11:08,009 --> 00:11:11,298
brutally killing 16 innocent Americans,

137
00:11:11,299 --> 00:11:14,298
leaving the U.S. military no choice

138
00:11:14,299 --> 00:11:16,799
but to take action.

139
00:11:18,801 --> 00:11:23,298
Nearly 5,000 American troops
cross the Mexican border

140
00:11:23,299 --> 00:11:25,298
to take down Villa.

141
00:11:25,299 --> 00:11:30,298
But fighting a guerrilla
force with a traditional army

142
00:11:30,299 --> 00:11:32,799
is next to impossible.

143
00:11:39,634 --> 00:11:42,799
[Gunshot]

144
00:11:44,299 --> 00:11:47,799
One army Captain is determined
to find a different way.

145
00:11:49,299 --> 00:11:53,799
His name is George S. Patton.

146
00:12:00,467 --> 00:12:03,299
Patton's ancestors fought
in the Revolutionary War;

147
00:12:03,300 --> 00:12:05,298
they fought in the Civil War.

148
00:12:05,299 --> 00:12:07,298
He grew up wanting to be a military hero.

149
00:12:07,299 --> 00:12:11,008
He has a reputation for being smart, tough,

150
00:12:11,009 --> 00:12:13,298
and for being ruthless.

151
00:12:13,299 --> 00:12:15,298
And he has another quality that's essential

152
00:12:15,299 --> 00:12:18,298
in military leadership.

153
00:12:18,299 --> 00:12:19,800
He understands the power of technology,

154
00:12:19,801 --> 00:12:23,298
and he doesn't want to fight
with cavalry and with horses.

155
00:12:23,299 --> 00:12:25,633
He's looking for new technology

156
00:12:25,634 --> 00:12:28,298
that will change the
nature of the battlefield.

157
00:12:28,299 --> 00:12:31,799
So the car is fairly new.

158
00:12:33,299 --> 00:12:37,175
If you strap a gun to a car,

159
00:12:37,176 --> 00:12:39,799
you've got a new instrument of warfare.

160
00:12:41,299 --> 00:12:44,299
Narrator: What Patton doesn't know

161
00:12:44,300 --> 00:12:47,799
is that he's about to
revolutionize warfare.

162
00:12:54,299 --> 00:12:56,800
I think Patton knew only one direction,

163
00:12:56,801 --> 00:12:58,298
and that was forward.

164
00:12:58,299 --> 00:13:00,298
He had a lot of charisma.

165
00:13:00,299 --> 00:13:02,633
He was a very colorful leader.

166
00:13:02,634 --> 00:13:05,298
I thought he was very egotistical,

167
00:13:05,299 --> 00:13:08,298
and that's fine as long
as you translate that

168
00:13:08,299 --> 00:13:09,800
into good leadership.

169
00:13:09,801 --> 00:13:13,332
But maybe a little bit over the top.

170
00:13:16,299 --> 00:13:18,298
Narrator: Almost immediately,

171
00:13:18,299 --> 00:13:22,175
Patton is able to put
his plan into action...

172
00:13:22,176 --> 00:13:25,799
[Motor rumbling]

173
00:13:28,299 --> 00:13:32,799
And he launches a surprise
raid on Pancho Villa's camp.

174
00:13:33,299 --> 00:13:34,799
Faster!

175
00:13:37,299 --> 00:13:39,799
Got 'em on the run. Go!

176
00:13:46,299 --> 00:13:48,799
Faster!

177
00:13:51,299 --> 00:13:53,298
Get down!

178
00:13:53,299 --> 00:13:55,799
[Gunfire]

179
00:13:57,300 --> 00:13:59,799
Let's go, let's go!

180
00:14:12,299 --> 00:14:16,298
Narrator: The bandits are no match

181
00:14:16,299 --> 00:14:18,298
for Patton and his mobile army,

182
00:14:18,299 --> 00:14:22,175
and by the end of the fight,

183
00:14:22,176 --> 00:14:25,298
three of villa's men have been killed,

184
00:14:25,299 --> 00:14:29,298
including his second-in-command.

185
00:14:29,299 --> 00:14:31,298
The first use of motorized warfare

186
00:14:31,299 --> 00:14:33,298
by the United States army

187
00:14:33,299 --> 00:14:37,298
is a huge success,

188
00:14:37,299 --> 00:14:39,298
and for Patton,

189
00:14:39,299 --> 00:14:43,799
it's the first step in
his rise to greatness.

190
00:14:47,299 --> 00:14:50,298
Half a world away,

191
00:14:50,299 --> 00:14:53,799
two massive armies collide
on the battlefield...

192
00:14:57,299 --> 00:15:00,799
In the first major war
with modern technology.

193
00:15:03,299 --> 00:15:04,633
When you look at World War I,

194
00:15:04,634 --> 00:15:07,298
it's about machine guns, and, you know,

195
00:15:07,299 --> 00:15:11,298
all of these sorts of
new killing mechanisms.

196
00:15:11,299 --> 00:15:15,298
It's the beginning of the
20th century as a tech era.

197
00:15:15,299 --> 00:15:18,147
This is not men on horseback anymore.

198
00:15:18,148 --> 00:15:20,676
This is a motorized war.

199
00:15:21,300 --> 00:15:24,899
Narrator: The advanced
weaponry turns the conflict

200
00:15:24,900 --> 00:15:26,899
into a slaughter.

201
00:15:26,900 --> 00:15:30,399
230 men are killed each hour...

202
00:15:32,899 --> 00:15:36,400
one death every 15 seconds.

203
00:15:36,401 --> 00:15:39,898
Really the machine gun probably
did more than anything else.

204
00:15:39,899 --> 00:15:43,898
They found if they dug
even shallow trenches

205
00:15:43,899 --> 00:15:44,898
and used machine guns,

206
00:15:44,899 --> 00:15:47,898
a small number of troops

207
00:15:47,899 --> 00:15:49,898
could stop a large attacking force.

208
00:15:49,899 --> 00:15:52,898
And then both sides
started to dig trenches.

209
00:15:52,899 --> 00:15:55,898
And so they were locked along
this line, the Western front,

210
00:15:55,899 --> 00:15:59,898
which was this extraordinarily
complex set of trenches

211
00:15:59,899 --> 00:16:03,898
that didn't move very much either way.

212
00:16:03,899 --> 00:16:05,202
[Explosion]

213
00:16:05,203 --> 00:16:07,800
Narrator: The trenches cover 25,000 miles.

214
00:16:07,801 --> 00:16:10,298
Laid end to end,

215
00:16:10,299 --> 00:16:12,967
they would circle the globe.

216
00:16:16,299 --> 00:16:20,298
The area between the trenches is so deadly,

217
00:16:20,299 --> 00:16:22,799
it's known...

218
00:16:24,299 --> 00:16:27,799
As no-man's-land.

219
00:16:40,801 --> 00:16:42,988
Among the German soldiers

220
00:16:42,989 --> 00:16:47,788
stationed in the trenches
along the Western front

221
00:16:47,989 --> 00:16:50,489
is Adolf Hitler.

222
00:16:52,989 --> 00:16:55,988
But even after months on the front lines,

223
00:16:55,989 --> 00:16:58,489
Hitler's still seen as an outcast.

224
00:17:02,555 --> 00:17:04,156
Hitler was regarded by the other troops

225
00:17:04,157 --> 00:17:05,988
as something of a loner,

226
00:17:05,989 --> 00:17:08,988
something of a rather
peculiar eccentric person

227
00:17:08,989 --> 00:17:11,489
who kept to himself.

228
00:17:11,989 --> 00:17:15,323
Narrator: But what
Hitler lacks in popularity

229
00:17:15,324 --> 00:17:18,156
he makes up for in blind ambition.

230
00:17:18,157 --> 00:17:20,489
Runner!

231
00:17:21,324 --> 00:17:24,988
Command wants this taken
to the 3rd Battalion.

232
00:17:24,989 --> 00:17:27,366
- Now!
- Yes, sir.

233
00:17:28,989 --> 00:17:30,988
Hitler's role as a messenger

234
00:17:30,989 --> 00:17:34,988
was actually considered
perhaps the most dangerous task

235
00:17:34,989 --> 00:17:36,988
in trench warfare...

236
00:17:36,989 --> 00:17:41,865
running from trench to trench,
exposing himself to enemy fire.

237
00:17:41,866 --> 00:17:44,490
The mortality rate for messengers

238
00:17:44,491 --> 00:17:46,489
was quite significant.

239
00:17:48,866 --> 00:17:51,489
Pull back!

240
00:18:10,324 --> 00:18:12,489
[Grunts]

241
00:18:16,989 --> 00:18:20,489
[Gunfire]

242
00:18:41,990 --> 00:18:44,489
[Explosion]

243
00:18:44,989 --> 00:18:48,489
[High-pitched ringing]

244
00:18:49,989 --> 00:18:52,988
[Dramatic string music]

245
00:18:52,989 --> 00:19:01,489
♪ ♪

246
00:19:26,699 --> 00:19:27,988
The Germans are retreating,

247
00:19:27,989 --> 00:19:29,490
and Adolf Hitler has been injured,

248
00:19:29,491 --> 00:19:34,988
and he has this encounter
with a Private Henry Tandey,

249
00:19:34,989 --> 00:19:36,490
a British Private.

250
00:19:43,989 --> 00:19:47,489
[Music swells]

251
00:19:54,989 --> 00:19:58,988
Tandey has Adolf Hitler in his sights,

252
00:19:58,989 --> 00:20:02,751
and even though he's a trained soldier,

253
00:20:02,752 --> 00:20:06,790
he can't bring himself to pull the trigger.

254
00:20:10,989 --> 00:20:13,988
If Tandey had pulled the trigger,

255
00:20:13,989 --> 00:20:18,865
Adolf Hitler would have died on
the battlefields in World War I,

256
00:20:18,866 --> 00:20:21,988
and the whole course of human
history would have been changed.

257
00:20:21,989 --> 00:20:24,489
It's one of the great what-ifs in history.

258
00:20:36,494 --> 00:20:38,493
Narrator: The World Wars have begun

259
00:20:38,494 --> 00:20:40,493
with Britain, France, and Russia

260
00:20:40,494 --> 00:20:43,493
squaring off against Germany
and the Central Powers.

261
00:20:43,494 --> 00:20:44,493
[Gunfire]

262
00:20:44,494 --> 00:20:47,500
Modern weaponry is causing mass devastation

263
00:20:47,501 --> 00:20:49,493
on the battlefields,

264
00:20:49,494 --> 00:20:51,493
and tens of thousands of soldiers

265
00:20:51,494 --> 00:20:53,994
are now living in overcrowded trenches.

266
00:20:55,494 --> 00:20:57,493
Very soon after the war began,

267
00:20:57,494 --> 00:21:03,720
both sides realized, "we can entrench,
and the other side can't move us out.

268
00:21:03,721 --> 00:21:06,370
"They can move us backwards a little bit

269
00:21:06,371 --> 00:21:09,087
but only at horrendous cost."

270
00:21:09,088 --> 00:21:11,087
And the result of this,

271
00:21:11,088 --> 00:21:14,589
the war just bogged down in
the muds of northern France.

272
00:21:23,088 --> 00:21:25,087
Narrator: But in London,

273
00:21:25,088 --> 00:21:27,589
one man is convinced he
can break the stalemate.

274
00:21:30,088 --> 00:21:33,087
He comes up to the barman and says...

275
00:21:33,088 --> 00:21:36,647
Narrator: Born into one of the
wealthiest families in Britain,

276
00:21:38,088 --> 00:21:41,588
he's risen through the
ranks at unusual speed...

277
00:21:43,088 --> 00:21:46,588
To become the head of the British Navy.

278
00:21:48,088 --> 00:21:52,087
His name is Winston Churchill.

279
00:21:52,088 --> 00:21:56,087
Churchill had the most
enormous self-confidence,

280
00:21:56,088 --> 00:21:58,087
and it's easy to see why that was the case.

281
00:21:58,088 --> 00:22:01,087
He was the son of Lord Randolph Churchill,

282
00:22:01,088 --> 00:22:02,462
who was a brilliant politician.

283
00:22:02,463 --> 00:22:05,087
And so Churchill, from a very young man,

284
00:22:05,088 --> 00:22:08,087
saw himself, almost by divine right,

285
00:22:08,088 --> 00:22:11,842
as playing a leading role in politics.

286
00:22:15,088 --> 00:22:18,087
Narrator: Churchill forms a bold plan

287
00:22:18,088 --> 00:22:22,087
that he's certain will
change the Allies' fortunes.

288
00:22:22,088 --> 00:22:24,087
He even at that point

289
00:22:24,088 --> 00:22:26,087
considered himself a strategist,

290
00:22:26,088 --> 00:22:30,087
and he looked for ways to break
the stalemate in Western Europe

291
00:22:30,088 --> 00:22:32,087
rather than just to get more
armies and more artillery,

292
00:22:32,088 --> 00:22:34,088
and it actually was fairly thoughtful.

293
00:22:34,089 --> 00:22:36,087
What if we could send a fleet

294
00:22:36,088 --> 00:22:40,087
to the south into the Black Sea?

295
00:22:40,088 --> 00:22:41,087
Resupply the Russians?

296
00:22:41,088 --> 00:22:44,087
Well, yes, exactly.

297
00:22:44,088 --> 00:22:46,087
There's no way.

298
00:22:46,088 --> 00:22:47,087
Well, yes, there is.

299
00:22:47,088 --> 00:22:50,087
Through Gallipoli.

300
00:22:50,088 --> 00:22:52,087
Gallipoli? No.

301
00:22:52,088 --> 00:22:54,087
This is our way in.

302
00:22:54,088 --> 00:22:57,087
With all due respect, we are
here to provide information...

303
00:22:57,088 --> 00:23:01,087
this is what we are doing.

304
00:23:01,088 --> 00:23:02,697
A lot of people Churchill worked with

305
00:23:02,698 --> 00:23:04,087
thought he was a man of contradictions,

306
00:23:04,088 --> 00:23:06,087
a Maverick, a loose cannon.

307
00:23:06,088 --> 00:23:08,087
He was known as someone to watch.

308
00:23:08,088 --> 00:23:09,797
His friends would say someone to watch

309
00:23:09,798 --> 00:23:11,087
because he's very talented,

310
00:23:11,088 --> 00:23:13,087
and his enemies would say someone to watch

311
00:23:13,088 --> 00:23:14,588
because he was dangerous.

312
00:23:15,766 --> 00:23:17,087
Narrator: The Gallipoli peninsula

313
00:23:17,088 --> 00:23:21,087
is heavily guarded by the Central Powers.

314
00:23:21,088 --> 00:23:24,630
Churchill's plan is to blast
through the narrow strait,

315
00:23:25,647 --> 00:23:30,087
Pushing through to Russia and
allowing the Allies to launch

316
00:23:30,088 --> 00:23:33,087
an overwhelming attack from the east,

317
00:23:33,088 --> 00:23:35,588
opening up a second front against Germany.

318
00:23:36,798 --> 00:23:38,087
If it's successful,

319
00:23:38,088 --> 00:23:42,087
the Allies will be able
to turn the tide of the war

320
00:23:42,088 --> 00:23:44,588
and crush the Central Powers.

321
00:23:49,590 --> 00:23:53,087
More than 100 warships set sail

322
00:23:53,088 --> 00:23:56,087
for what will be the
largest amphibious invasion

323
00:23:56,088 --> 00:23:58,588
the world has ever seen.

324
00:24:06,088 --> 00:24:09,087
[Pensive orchestral music]

325
00:24:09,088 --> 00:24:13,087
♪ ♪

326
00:24:13,088 --> 00:24:15,087
People often ask me, "what's the most

327
00:24:15,088 --> 00:24:17,087
difficult decision you've ever made?"

328
00:24:17,088 --> 00:24:20,286
It's always the decision
of sending men into battle,

329
00:24:20,287 --> 00:24:21,996
and the worst part of it all

330
00:24:21,997 --> 00:24:24,286
is the night that the battle begins,

331
00:24:24,287 --> 00:24:27,240
because you know you've
just launched something,

332
00:24:27,241 --> 00:24:31,050
and you know that within a few hours

333
00:24:31,287 --> 00:24:33,286
you will start getting
calls from the battlefield,

334
00:24:33,287 --> 00:24:35,286
from your commanders out in the field,

335
00:24:35,287 --> 00:24:38,996
that will tell you how
many young men have died.

336
00:24:38,997 --> 00:24:41,787
[Telephone rings]

337
00:24:44,287 --> 00:24:48,286
Yes?

338
00:24:48,287 --> 00:24:50,286
They're halfway up the straits.

339
00:24:50,287 --> 00:24:51,824
They should have broken through by now.

340
00:24:51,825 --> 00:24:52,673
They'll make it.

341
00:24:52,674 --> 00:24:54,673
Four ships sunk.

342
00:24:54,674 --> 00:24:56,673
Another burning.

343
00:24:56,674 --> 00:24:59,383
Losses were to be expected.

344
00:24:59,384 --> 00:25:01,383
The fleet is requesting
permission to turn back.

345
00:25:01,384 --> 00:25:05,174
They are to press on at all costs.

346
00:25:06,674 --> 00:25:08,174
This is war.

347
00:25:11,674 --> 00:25:14,673
Gallipoli I don't think
could ever have worked.

348
00:25:14,674 --> 00:25:16,673
The troops who stormed ashore

349
00:25:16,674 --> 00:25:20,673
were met by a hail of machine
gun fire and artillery,

350
00:25:20,674 --> 00:25:23,174
and the casualties were appalling.

351
00:25:27,674 --> 00:25:32,673
Narrator: The invasion
is a devastating failure.

352
00:25:32,674 --> 00:25:37,673
56,000 Allied troops are killed

353
00:25:37,674 --> 00:25:42,174
and nearly 200,000 are
reported injured or missing.

354
00:25:43,674 --> 00:25:46,174
Almost no ground is gained...

355
00:25:48,674 --> 00:25:51,673
And the supply route to Russia

356
00:25:51,674 --> 00:25:54,673
remains closed off.

357
00:25:54,674 --> 00:25:57,673
I think Churchill's
credibility after Gallipoli

358
00:25:57,674 --> 00:26:01,174
was certainly called into question.

359
00:26:03,674 --> 00:26:06,673
Warfare is not a science.

360
00:26:06,674 --> 00:26:08,673
The one thing you do know
when you commit to warfare is,

361
00:26:08,674 --> 00:26:11,174
it's gonna be horrible.

362
00:26:12,674 --> 00:26:15,934
Narrator: The public is
outraged by the carnage.

363
00:26:17,984 --> 00:26:20,862
Someone will have to take the blame.

364
00:26:29,674 --> 00:26:33,673
It's over.

365
00:26:33,674 --> 00:26:35,673
The plan was sound.

366
00:26:35,674 --> 00:26:36,673
Excuse me?

367
00:26:36,674 --> 00:26:37,673
The plan was sound.

368
00:26:37,674 --> 00:26:39,673
All we needed to do was
keep pushing forward.

369
00:26:39,674 --> 00:26:40,673
I'm afraid your services

370
00:26:40,674 --> 00:26:43,673
as First Lord of the Admiralty

371
00:26:43,674 --> 00:26:47,673
are no longer required.

372
00:26:47,674 --> 00:26:52,174
I'll expect your letter of
resignation in the morning.

373
00:27:04,009 --> 00:27:05,673
When Churchill was let go,

374
00:27:05,674 --> 00:27:09,174
he thought his career was over, finished.

375
00:27:10,674 --> 00:27:12,673
And that wasn't melodrama on his part,

376
00:27:12,674 --> 00:27:14,081
and he could be melodramatic.

377
00:27:14,082 --> 00:27:15,780
It appeared that it would be finished.

378
00:27:15,781 --> 00:27:18,673
It's hard to imagine Churchill

379
00:27:18,674 --> 00:27:20,673
being humbled by something like Gallipoli,

380
00:27:20,674 --> 00:27:22,673
but he was chastened.

381
00:27:22,674 --> 00:27:25,673
He thought, "never again.

382
00:27:25,674 --> 00:27:28,242
"The next time, if there's a next time"...

383
00:27:28,243 --> 00:27:30,000
and it didn't look like there would be...

384
00:27:30,001 --> 00:27:32,174
"I'll do it right."

385
00:27:39,674 --> 00:27:43,673
Narrator: Defeated and humiliated,

386
00:27:43,674 --> 00:27:46,174
Churchill's career is all but ruined.

387
00:27:51,009 --> 00:27:53,673
He's offered a desk job

388
00:27:53,674 --> 00:27:56,174
which he turns down.

389
00:27:58,674 --> 00:28:01,673
He knows if he's ever
going to redeem himself,

390
00:28:01,674 --> 00:28:04,174
he needs a new path.

391
00:28:09,674 --> 00:28:12,673
So Churchill does the unthinkable.

392
00:28:12,674 --> 00:28:15,174
He enlists in the British army...

393
00:28:17,674 --> 00:28:20,174
And heads straight for the front lines.

394
00:28:24,674 --> 00:28:27,673
While Winston Churchill
looks for redemption,

395
00:28:27,674 --> 00:28:30,673
Germany looks to capitalize
on its victory at Gallipoli,

396
00:28:30,674 --> 00:28:33,673
devising a plan to
eliminate the Russian threat

397
00:28:33,674 --> 00:28:36,174
once and for all.

398
00:28:40,674 --> 00:28:42,673
The Germans load a secret weapon

399
00:28:42,674 --> 00:28:48,174
onto a heavily guarded
train headed for Russia.

400
00:28:48,674 --> 00:28:51,673
[Dramatic orchestral music]

401
00:28:51,674 --> 00:28:52,673
♪ ♪

402
00:28:52,674 --> 00:28:54,673
It's a weapon that promises

403
00:28:54,674 --> 00:28:58,174
to destroy their enemies
from the inside out.

404
00:29:02,674 --> 00:29:06,174
[Whistle blowing]

405
00:29:07,674 --> 00:29:12,174
That weapon is Vladimir Lenin.

406
00:29:17,674 --> 00:29:22,673
Lenin is the leader of Russia's
Communist Revolutionaries

407
00:29:22,674 --> 00:29:25,174
hell-bent on toppling the Russian Czar.

408
00:29:27,551 --> 00:29:28,673
For the past ten years,

409
00:29:28,674 --> 00:29:31,673
he's been in exile in Switzerland

410
00:29:31,674 --> 00:29:35,673
until Germany sends him home on a train

411
00:29:35,674 --> 00:29:37,673
along with over $10 million

412
00:29:37,674 --> 00:29:39,175
to fund his revolution.

413
00:29:40,674 --> 00:29:41,673
The Germans decided

414
00:29:41,674 --> 00:29:43,673
that they would take this enormous gamble

415
00:29:43,674 --> 00:29:46,673
and bring Lenin back to Russia

416
00:29:46,674 --> 00:29:49,673
to bring about a revolution
to get Russia out the war.

417
00:29:49,674 --> 00:29:52,174
That's about as radical
a step as you can take.

418
00:29:56,674 --> 00:29:59,673
Narrator: When Lenin gets to Moscow,

419
00:29:59,674 --> 00:30:02,673
he's greeted by an old friend.

420
00:30:02,674 --> 00:30:05,673
Six times he's been exiled to Siberia,

421
00:30:05,674 --> 00:30:08,673
and six times he's escaped.

422
00:30:08,674 --> 00:30:12,174
His name is Joseph Stalin.

423
00:30:14,674 --> 00:30:16,673
Comrade.

424
00:30:16,674 --> 00:30:18,673
Comrade.

425
00:30:18,674 --> 00:30:21,673
Let me show you to your new place.

426
00:30:21,674 --> 00:30:22,673
Narrator: Reunited,

427
00:30:22,674 --> 00:30:25,673
the two play right into Germany's plan

428
00:30:25,674 --> 00:30:28,673
as they begin to plot an armed rebellion.

429
00:30:28,674 --> 00:30:30,673
Over the next few months,

430
00:30:30,674 --> 00:30:35,673
Lenin and Stalin recruit
a massive workers' militia.

431
00:30:35,674 --> 00:30:39,673
Using the $10 million
from the German government,

432
00:30:39,674 --> 00:30:44,174
they quietly amass a
stockpile of weapons...

433
00:30:45,674 --> 00:30:48,673
Until they are ready to make their move.

434
00:30:48,674 --> 00:30:50,673
I've arranged to take the train stations

435
00:30:50,674 --> 00:30:53,673
and the telephone communications.

436
00:30:53,674 --> 00:30:54,673
And the palace guard?

437
00:30:54,674 --> 00:30:56,673
Many of our sources

438
00:30:56,674 --> 00:30:59,673
say they are sympathetic to our cause.

439
00:30:59,674 --> 00:31:04,174
Our timing has to be perfect.

440
00:31:14,674 --> 00:31:17,673
Narrator: The Communists
storm the Winter Palace,

441
00:31:17,674 --> 00:31:20,673
toppling the Russian Czar.

442
00:31:20,674 --> 00:31:24,174
The Soviet union is born.

443
00:31:30,674 --> 00:31:33,174
This is just the beginning, comrade.

444
00:31:36,674 --> 00:31:39,673
Narrator: Just days later,

445
00:31:39,674 --> 00:31:45,174
Lenin signs a decree that
takes Russia out of the war.

446
00:31:46,674 --> 00:31:49,673
The German plan works,

447
00:31:49,674 --> 00:31:54,174
bringing them one step closer to victory.

448
00:31:57,237 --> 00:31:59,236
Narrator: Europe is at war,

449
00:31:59,237 --> 00:32:02,236
and in a bold move, the Central Powers

450
00:32:02,237 --> 00:32:04,236
have ended the fighting
on the eastern front,

451
00:32:04,237 --> 00:32:10,236
sending exiled revolutionary
Vladimir Lenin back to Russia

452
00:32:10,237 --> 00:32:13,236
where he seized control of the country

453
00:32:13,237 --> 00:32:16,072
and took the Russian army out of the fight.

454
00:32:19,237 --> 00:32:23,236
Germany can turn its
attention to the other Allies,

455
00:32:23,237 --> 00:32:26,113
and one of the countries
now forced to fend off

456
00:32:26,114 --> 00:32:28,571
a new wave of German soldiers

457
00:32:28,572 --> 00:32:32,236
is Italy.

458
00:32:32,237 --> 00:32:35,236
Italy joined the fight in 1915

459
00:32:35,237 --> 00:32:38,236
and now must face the full
might of the German army

460
00:32:38,237 --> 00:32:40,236
for the first time.

461
00:32:40,237 --> 00:32:42,236
Tens of thousands of troops

462
00:32:42,237 --> 00:32:44,777
are rushed to defend the
Italian border in the alps.

463
00:32:50,572 --> 00:32:53,946
Among them

464
00:32:53,947 --> 00:32:57,737
is a sharpshooter named Benito Mussolini.

465
00:33:00,405 --> 00:33:03,236
Before the war, Mussolini
is an antiwar activist.

466
00:33:03,237 --> 00:33:06,700
He's a journalist. He's
pretty much a pacifist.

467
00:33:19,237 --> 00:33:21,737
[Gunshot]

468
00:33:24,947 --> 00:33:27,236
Narrator: The time spent
defending Italy's border

469
00:33:27,237 --> 00:33:32,736
makes Mussolini hungry to
return Italy to greatness.

470
00:33:32,739 --> 00:33:34,905
[Gunshot]

471
00:33:36,237 --> 00:33:38,236
Mussolini becomes a very different person

472
00:33:38,237 --> 00:33:40,113
than he was before the war.

473
00:33:40,114 --> 00:33:42,236
His whole attitude toward his nation

474
00:33:42,237 --> 00:33:44,236
and his role in it changes.

475
00:33:44,237 --> 00:33:46,885
He develops this hyper
sense of nationalism,

476
00:33:46,886 --> 00:33:50,236
this real pride in his country.

477
00:33:50,237 --> 00:33:52,236
Narrator: The horrors of war

478
00:33:52,237 --> 00:33:56,872
have transformed Mussolini
into a ruthless killing machine.

479
00:33:57,237 --> 00:34:01,622
A trait he'll take back with him to Rome.

480
00:34:02,572 --> 00:34:04,236
[Gunshot]

481
00:34:04,237 --> 00:34:07,236
600 miles to the north in Belgium,

482
00:34:07,237 --> 00:34:09,236
the British army digs in...

483
00:34:09,237 --> 00:34:12,436
[Gunfire]

484
00:34:19,369 --> 00:34:21,236
Since the beginning of the war,

485
00:34:21,237 --> 00:34:25,236
nearly 400,000 British
soldiers have been killed

486
00:34:25,237 --> 00:34:28,737
just to be replaced by new arrivals.

487
00:34:32,237 --> 00:34:34,236
Among the new recruits

488
00:34:34,237 --> 00:34:35,237
is a man battling back

489
00:34:35,238 --> 00:34:38,737
from the biggest failure of his life...

490
00:34:41,237 --> 00:34:43,236
Winston Churchill.

491
00:34:43,237 --> 00:34:45,236
Churchill took responsibility

492
00:34:45,237 --> 00:34:49,236
for everything he ever did in his life.

493
00:34:49,237 --> 00:34:51,236
He never passed the buck.

494
00:34:51,237 --> 00:34:54,946
He was humbled, humiliated by Gallipoli,

495
00:34:54,947 --> 00:34:56,236
and he had to do something,

496
00:34:56,237 --> 00:34:58,236
and he put himself in harm's way

497
00:34:58,237 --> 00:35:01,236
and volunteered to go to the trenches.

498
00:35:01,237 --> 00:35:02,946
It was a very dangerous thing to do.

499
00:35:02,947 --> 00:35:05,236
[Explosion]

500
00:35:05,237 --> 00:35:07,236
- Move!
- Go!

501
00:35:07,237 --> 00:35:09,737
[Explosions, gunfire]

502
00:35:11,238 --> 00:35:13,236
Sir,

503
00:35:13,237 --> 00:35:15,946
2nd Platoon lost this main trench.

504
00:35:15,947 --> 00:35:18,737
Get me the Mortar Team
from the West Reserve now.

505
00:35:37,739 --> 00:35:40,236
You get the hell scared
out of you first of all.

506
00:35:40,237 --> 00:35:44,236
The first time I got shot at, um, was,

507
00:35:44,237 --> 00:35:46,946
"hey, this isn't a game. This is for real.

508
00:35:46,947 --> 00:35:48,571
This guy really missed me,

509
00:35:48,572 --> 00:35:50,236
and he killed somebody else.

510
00:35:50,237 --> 00:35:52,236
But tomorrow he'll try to kill me."

511
00:35:52,237 --> 00:35:53,236
[Gunshot]

512
00:35:53,237 --> 00:35:56,738
As we say in the military,
that opens your nostrils.

513
00:36:02,947 --> 00:36:05,236
Narrator: With British
casualties escalating,

514
00:36:05,237 --> 00:36:09,236
Churchill is quickly promoted

515
00:36:09,237 --> 00:36:11,236
and discovers he has what it takes

516
00:36:11,237 --> 00:36:13,737
to lead men into battle.

517
00:36:18,114 --> 00:36:20,236
For a man of Churchill's ambition,

518
00:36:20,237 --> 00:36:23,737
it's the first step towards redemption.

519
00:36:26,114 --> 00:36:28,236
In his heart, what
Churchill always wanted to be

520
00:36:28,237 --> 00:36:30,737
was the great warrior, the great hero.

521
00:36:33,237 --> 00:36:37,404
Here he was commanding a mere 800 men,

522
00:36:37,405 --> 00:36:39,571
whereas he dreamed of directing

523
00:36:39,572 --> 00:36:42,737
the battle destinies of millions.

524
00:37:00,238 --> 00:37:03,236
Narrator: The fight seems unending...

525
00:37:03,237 --> 00:37:06,236
Mail!

526
00:37:06,237 --> 00:37:10,738
Narrator: Until Germany
unleashes a secret weapon.

527
00:37:10,739 --> 00:37:13,236
Incoming!

528
00:37:13,237 --> 00:37:16,236
[Explosion, gas hissing]

529
00:37:16,237 --> 00:37:17,237
Gas!

530
00:37:17,238 --> 00:37:20,236
Move! Move!

531
00:37:20,237 --> 00:37:22,236
Out of the way!

532
00:37:22,237 --> 00:37:23,236
Go!

533
00:37:23,237 --> 00:37:25,236
[All coughing]

534
00:37:25,237 --> 00:37:28,236
Go, go, go, go!

535
00:37:28,237 --> 00:37:31,737
[All coughing]

536
00:37:54,817 --> 00:37:58,640
The fight between the
Central and Allied powers

537
00:37:58,641 --> 00:38:01,975
has become the bloodiest
war in human history.

538
00:38:01,976 --> 00:38:03,640
By 1917,

539
00:38:03,641 --> 00:38:08,640
nearly 7 million British, French,
and German soldiers have been killed.

540
00:38:08,641 --> 00:38:11,460
- Gas!
- Go.

541
00:38:12,641 --> 00:38:16,141
[All coughing]

542
00:38:17,641 --> 00:38:19,350
It was a war of attrition.

543
00:38:19,351 --> 00:38:21,640
You had to kill as many
of the enemy as you could

544
00:38:21,641 --> 00:38:23,640
so you could possibly advance.

545
00:38:23,641 --> 00:38:25,640
Chemical warfare just enabled that

546
00:38:25,641 --> 00:38:30,640
in a very horrific way.

547
00:38:30,641 --> 00:38:34,142
For a way to alter the course of the war.

548
00:38:34,143 --> 00:38:35,975
So they look to the one country

549
00:38:35,976 --> 00:38:39,851
that could finally tip
the scales in their favor.

550
00:38:48,641 --> 00:38:51,640
Until now, President Woodrow Wilson

551
00:38:51,641 --> 00:38:55,640
has kept America out of the war.

552
00:38:55,641 --> 00:38:58,640
Wilson recognized that the American people

553
00:38:58,641 --> 00:39:00,641
did not want to get involved in a war,

554
00:39:00,642 --> 00:39:03,640
particularly if it's a war
far away involving people

555
00:39:03,641 --> 00:39:07,640
and for causes that we
had nothing to do with.

556
00:39:07,641 --> 00:39:10,640
Frankly, the American
people did not see themselves

557
00:39:10,641 --> 00:39:12,641
at immediate risk.

558
00:39:12,642 --> 00:39:15,640
Narrator: But with hostilities escalating,

559
00:39:15,641 --> 00:39:20,046
a peaceful solution seems
less and less likely,

560
00:39:20,123 --> 00:39:22,909
and Wilson's advisors urge him

561
00:39:22,910 --> 00:39:26,141
to begin preparing military forces.

562
00:39:27,641 --> 00:39:33,640
Among them is the 35-year-old
Assistant Secretary of the Navy

563
00:39:33,641 --> 00:39:35,640
Franklin Delano Roosevelt.

564
00:39:35,641 --> 00:39:37,640
Mr. President, I recommend
an immediate allocation

565
00:39:37,641 --> 00:39:39,640
of more funds to our naval resources

566
00:39:39,641 --> 00:39:42,975
if we want to maintain
military preparedness.

567
00:39:42,976 --> 00:39:47,808
Wilson found himself being
drawn closer and closer to war.

568
00:39:47,809 --> 00:39:49,640
In the spring of 1915,

569
00:39:49,641 --> 00:39:51,640
the British liner the lusitania was sunk,

570
00:39:51,641 --> 00:39:53,640
and on board were over a hundred Americans.

571
00:39:53,641 --> 00:39:55,640
Now, this was a big deal.

572
00:39:55,641 --> 00:39:57,975
Until this time, it
had been a European war.

573
00:39:57,976 --> 00:39:59,640
But now in this European war,

574
00:39:59,641 --> 00:40:02,640
Americans were getting killed.

575
00:40:02,641 --> 00:40:05,640
Narrator: American resentment
grows against Germany,

576
00:40:05,641 --> 00:40:09,640
and on February 26, 1917,

577
00:40:09,641 --> 00:40:13,142
it to finally reaches a boiling point.

578
00:40:13,143 --> 00:40:16,141
Mr. President, I think you
should look at this right away.

579
00:40:26,641 --> 00:40:28,640
Narrator: The United States intercepts

580
00:40:28,641 --> 00:40:31,640
a secret telegram from Germany

581
00:40:31,641 --> 00:40:34,640
intended for the Mexican government

582
00:40:34,641 --> 00:40:37,476
containing a shocking proposal.

583
00:40:38,641 --> 00:40:40,640
The Germans are offering to fund

584
00:40:40,641 --> 00:40:43,641
a Mexican invasion of the United States

585
00:40:43,642 --> 00:40:47,640
that would allow the country
to reclaim the border states

586
00:40:47,641 --> 00:40:52,141
of Arizona, New Mexico, and Texas.

587
00:40:53,641 --> 00:40:55,142
The German ploy was,

588
00:40:55,143 --> 00:40:58,593
preoccupy America with a war with Mexico,

589
00:40:58,594 --> 00:41:01,201
and therefore you keep them out of Europe.

590
00:41:01,202 --> 00:41:03,640
Well, this incensed a lot of Americans,

591
00:41:03,641 --> 00:41:05,640
and rightfully so.

592
00:41:05,641 --> 00:41:07,640
Narrator: The U.S. government
releases the contents

593
00:41:07,641 --> 00:41:09,350
of the secret message,

594
00:41:09,351 --> 00:41:10,640
and almost instantly,

595
00:41:10,641 --> 00:41:14,640
anti-German protests
erupt all across America.

596
00:41:14,641 --> 00:41:16,350
The Zimmermann telegram

597
00:41:16,351 --> 00:41:18,350
was one of the stupidest things

598
00:41:18,351 --> 00:41:19,640
the German government ever did.

599
00:41:19,641 --> 00:41:21,640
Texas didn't care about the war in Europe.

600
00:41:21,641 --> 00:41:23,640
Now all of a sudden,

601
00:41:23,641 --> 00:41:26,640
the Germans are trying
to return Texas to Mexico?

602
00:41:26,641 --> 00:41:27,640
Enough with Germany.

603
00:41:27,641 --> 00:41:30,640
They need to be taught a lesson.

604
00:41:30,641 --> 00:41:33,640
Narrator: President Wilson
signs the declaration of war

605
00:41:33,641 --> 00:41:36,640
in April of 1917.

606
00:41:36,641 --> 00:41:39,640
Germany's plan to keep
America out of Europe

607
00:41:39,641 --> 00:41:42,141
completely backfires.

608
00:41:43,641 --> 00:41:46,640
The Americans may finally be ready for war,

609
00:41:46,641 --> 00:41:49,851
but their military isn't.

610
00:41:50,641 --> 00:41:53,142
The U.S. has a standing army

611
00:41:53,143 --> 00:41:54,975
of only 100,000 men

612
00:41:54,976 --> 00:41:59,640
while the German army has 4 1/2 million.

613
00:41:59,641 --> 00:42:03,946
The United States hurries
to build its military,

614
00:42:05,115 --> 00:42:09,141
and those few with fighting
experience are rushed to France.

615
00:42:21,143 --> 00:42:22,640
George S. Patton

616
00:42:22,641 --> 00:42:26,141
has been presented with a huge challenge...

617
00:42:27,809 --> 00:42:32,640
To command a Battalion of American men

618
00:42:32,641 --> 00:42:36,141
using the latest form
of military innovation...

619
00:42:44,641 --> 00:42:47,141
The tank.

620
00:42:52,641 --> 00:42:55,640
Some American Generals were
really resisting the tank

621
00:42:55,641 --> 00:42:58,641
because they didn't want to
get rid of the horse cavalry.

622
00:42:58,642 --> 00:43:02,640
George Patton understood the
power of the new technology

623
00:43:02,641 --> 00:43:04,640
of mobile and armed warfare,

624
00:43:04,641 --> 00:43:07,141
and he invested a lot in that.

625
00:43:11,642 --> 00:43:14,640
Narrator: The tank is already
being used on the Western front

626
00:43:14,641 --> 00:43:18,640
but with little success.

627
00:43:18,641 --> 00:43:21,142
It runs out of gas too quickly,

628
00:43:21,143 --> 00:43:23,517
gets stuck in the mud too easily,

629
00:43:23,518 --> 00:43:24,808
and its sheer size

630
00:43:24,809 --> 00:43:26,640
makes it difficult to incorporate

631
00:43:26,641 --> 00:43:29,640
in military maneuvers.

632
00:43:29,641 --> 00:43:34,640
But where others see an
insurmountable challenge,

633
00:43:34,641 --> 00:43:38,640
Patton sees a chance
to prove that his tanks

634
00:43:38,641 --> 00:43:42,640
can break the stalemate.

635
00:43:42,641 --> 00:43:45,640
I think innovation comes between the ears.

636
00:43:45,641 --> 00:43:47,640
It's not about the gizmo.

637
00:43:47,641 --> 00:43:50,427
It's about how you think about
using technology and so forth.

638
00:43:50,428 --> 00:43:52,985
You have to give credit
to the people like Patton

639
00:43:52,986 --> 00:43:55,481
that experienced World War I, that had been

640
00:43:55,482 --> 00:44:00,511
thinking about how to employ new things.

641
00:44:09,986 --> 00:44:11,986
Narrator: Patton knows the stakes are high.

642
00:44:11,987 --> 00:44:14,486
[Explosion]

643
00:44:15,696 --> 00:44:19,695
But with his Battalion of tanks,

644
00:44:19,696 --> 00:44:21,985
he's determined to win the war...

645
00:44:21,986 --> 00:44:23,320
[Explosion]

646
00:44:23,321 --> 00:44:26,363
Or die trying.

647
00:44:30,134 --> 00:44:32,301
Narrator: The global war rages in Europe...

648
00:44:32,302 --> 00:44:34,550
[Gunfire]

649
00:44:34,551 --> 00:44:39,909
As the Allies fight to hold their ground
against Germany and the Central Powers...

650
00:44:41,166 --> 00:44:43,666
in the sprawling system of trenches.

651
00:44:50,166 --> 00:44:53,165
Things are ugly in World War I.

652
00:44:53,166 --> 00:44:56,042
Europe was staggered, exhausted,

653
00:44:56,043 --> 00:44:57,165
many cities in rubble.

654
00:44:57,166 --> 00:45:01,165
Starvation and disease were widespread.

655
00:45:01,166 --> 00:45:03,165
You know, the Red Cross
couldn't even keep up

656
00:45:03,166 --> 00:45:05,165
with what was going on.

657
00:45:05,166 --> 00:45:07,680
If you were the Allies in Europe,

658
00:45:07,681 --> 00:45:09,891
you needed the reinforcements...

659
00:45:09,892 --> 00:45:12,341
The new energy, the new blood.

660
00:45:15,333 --> 00:45:21,083
To aid in the fight, the Allies
recruit a new country to their side.

661
00:45:21,876 --> 00:45:25,165
Following their long-awaited
entry into the war,

662
00:45:25,166 --> 00:45:28,376
America is ready to make its presence felt.

663
00:45:33,166 --> 00:45:35,165
Their first major offensive

664
00:45:35,166 --> 00:45:38,165
is an attack on the Western front

665
00:45:38,166 --> 00:45:40,165
hoping to force the Central Powers

666
00:45:40,166 --> 00:45:41,333
out of their trenches

667
00:45:41,334 --> 00:45:44,168
and drive them out of France.

668
00:45:45,166 --> 00:45:48,165
They're armed with a
secret weapon of their own:

669
00:45:48,166 --> 00:45:52,042
A Battalion of lightweight tanks

670
00:45:52,043 --> 00:45:54,333
under the command of
Colonel George S. Patton.

671
00:45:54,334 --> 00:45:56,165
In a column.

672
00:45:56,166 --> 00:45:59,165
We're gonna go down the main road.
Don't let anyone know we're coming.

673
00:45:59,166 --> 00:46:02,165
- We move at dawn.
- Yes, sir!

674
00:46:02,166 --> 00:46:04,165
Patton is testing his new strategy.

675
00:46:04,166 --> 00:46:07,165
He's leading this new
form of weaponry, the tank.

676
00:46:07,166 --> 00:46:10,165
So it's an important battle for him

677
00:46:10,166 --> 00:46:13,165
to prove that tanks are
valuable on the battlefield

678
00:46:13,166 --> 00:46:17,667
and also to establish himself
as an important military leader.

679
00:46:19,166 --> 00:46:20,875
Narrator: For Patton,

680
00:46:20,876 --> 00:46:24,165
everything in his career
has led up to this moment.

681
00:46:24,166 --> 00:46:26,166
George Patton had grown up to be a soldier.

682
00:46:26,167 --> 00:46:29,667
It was his identity.

683
00:46:29,668 --> 00:46:34,543
And so in the first World
War, he is in his element.

684
00:46:39,166 --> 00:46:41,666
[Engines roaring]

685
00:46:44,166 --> 00:46:46,666
[Distant explosions]

686
00:46:49,876 --> 00:46:53,165
Narrator: The night before
the planned invasion,

687
00:46:53,166 --> 00:46:56,165
Patton can't sleep.

688
00:46:56,166 --> 00:46:59,165
Tanks are still unproven in warfare,

689
00:46:59,166 --> 00:47:02,666
and Patton knows he can't
leave anything to chance.

690
00:47:17,166 --> 00:47:21,667
[Explosion, flare hissing]

691
00:47:21,668 --> 00:47:25,667
He slips out of the
trenches totally unprotected,

692
00:47:25,668 --> 00:47:29,165
deep into the heart
of no-man's-land.

693
00:47:29,166 --> 00:47:31,500
He's scouting a route

694
00:47:31,501 --> 00:47:34,666
to ensure his machines
won't get stuck in the mud.

695
00:47:39,166 --> 00:47:41,811
I think when you look at
someone like George Patton,

696
00:47:41,812 --> 00:47:43,513
he used intelligence well

697
00:47:43,623 --> 00:47:46,075
but I think the best thing he did was,

698
00:47:46,076 --> 00:47:48,733
he turned intelligence
into action, very quickly.

699
00:47:49,167 --> 00:47:53,165
George Patton's tendency was for action.

700
00:47:53,166 --> 00:47:55,165
Because he was aggressive,

701
00:47:55,166 --> 00:47:56,987
for him it worked very, very well.

702
00:48:14,166 --> 00:48:17,667
Narrator: On September 12, 1918,

703
00:48:17,668 --> 00:48:20,165
Patton and his forces
sweep onto the battlefield

704
00:48:20,166 --> 00:48:23,165
from every angle...

705
00:48:23,166 --> 00:48:26,666
[Explosions, gunfire]

706
00:48:31,166 --> 00:48:34,666
And the Germans hit back
with everything they've got.

707
00:48:42,166 --> 00:48:45,666
But all of Patton's
intelligence is paying off...

708
00:48:48,166 --> 00:48:51,666
And his Tank Brigade begins
to break down the German line.

709
00:49:08,334 --> 00:49:10,165
Soldier!

710
00:49:10,166 --> 00:49:12,165
- Get on the left flank now!
- Yes, sir.

711
00:49:12,166 --> 00:49:14,042
General, Charlie Company's advancing.

712
00:49:14,043 --> 00:49:15,917
- Take position on the Ridge.
- Yes, sir.

713
00:49:15,918 --> 00:49:18,752
Keep moving! Keep moving!

714
00:49:22,549 --> 00:49:23,749
Lieutenant George S. Patton,

715
00:49:23,750 --> 00:49:24,917
1st Tank Brigade.

716
00:49:24,918 --> 00:49:27,749
Brigadier General Douglas MacArthur,

717
00:49:27,750 --> 00:49:29,750
42nd Infantry.

718
00:49:29,751 --> 00:49:32,749
General, sir, they need you at the front.

719
00:49:32,750 --> 00:49:34,749
All right, boys!

720
00:49:34,750 --> 00:49:35,749
Let's move up!

721
00:49:35,750 --> 00:49:37,749
Patton and MacArthur.

722
00:49:37,750 --> 00:49:39,626
Here they are in Saint-Mihiel,

723
00:49:39,627 --> 00:49:41,749
and they meet on the
battlefield for the first time

724
00:49:41,750 --> 00:49:45,749
in the midst of artillery
shells all around them.

725
00:49:45,750 --> 00:49:47,084
You have these two men

726
00:49:47,085 --> 00:49:49,749
who are going to play
such an important role

727
00:49:49,750 --> 00:49:52,917
in shaping the future of the 20th century,

728
00:49:52,918 --> 00:49:57,250
and they have no idea what
history has in store for them.

729
00:50:00,750 --> 00:50:04,749
Narrator: MacArthur is from
a long line of military men.

730
00:50:04,750 --> 00:50:07,749
His father was awarded the
Congressional Medal of Honor

731
00:50:07,750 --> 00:50:10,749
in the American Civil War.

732
00:50:10,750 --> 00:50:13,917
No less is expected of his son.

733
00:50:13,918 --> 00:50:16,749
Douglas MacArthur would lead attacks

734
00:50:16,750 --> 00:50:21,251
walking out into
no-man's-land with a swagger.

735
00:50:21,252 --> 00:50:24,749
He was embodied with not
only tremendous ability

736
00:50:24,750 --> 00:50:26,251
but also tremendous self-confidence.

737
00:50:26,252 --> 00:50:27,749
Watch the right flank!

738
00:50:27,750 --> 00:50:29,749
From an early age,

739
00:50:29,750 --> 00:50:32,749
he was different.

740
00:50:32,750 --> 00:50:34,688
He was special.

741
00:50:34,689 --> 00:50:36,028
I don't want to say "anointed".

742
00:50:36,085 --> 00:50:38,250
But he may have thought he was.

743
00:50:42,750 --> 00:50:44,749
Narrator: The two West Point graduates

744
00:50:44,750 --> 00:50:48,251
will be allies and rivals for decades.

745
00:50:48,252 --> 00:50:49,749
I don't think there's any question

746
00:50:49,750 --> 00:50:52,224
that a leader who has experienced war

747
00:50:52,225 --> 00:50:53,955
and what it means to be in battle.

748
00:50:54,252 --> 00:50:56,459
If you're a military commander,

749
00:50:56,460 --> 00:50:58,585
that experience is invaluable.

750
00:50:59,750 --> 00:51:01,749
How you try to ensure that

751
00:51:01,750 --> 00:51:04,084
in the midst of all of that chaos

752
00:51:04,085 --> 00:51:06,084
and the killing that's going on,

753
00:51:06,085 --> 00:51:07,749
that you keep your eye on the mission

754
00:51:07,750 --> 00:51:11,604
that has to be accomplished,
that's not easy to do.

755
00:51:14,750 --> 00:51:17,749
[explosions, gunfire]

756
00:51:17,750 --> 00:51:22,749
Narrator: The two men
lead the Allies to victory

757
00:51:22,750 --> 00:51:24,585
as the German line crumbles.

758
00:51:28,252 --> 00:51:30,749
And for the first time,

759
00:51:30,750 --> 00:51:34,250
the Central Powers are on the run.

760
00:51:44,750 --> 00:51:48,216
Just 240 miles away,

761
00:51:48,416 --> 00:51:50,858
years of trench warfare have

762
00:51:50,859 --> 00:51:55,084
transformed Adolf Hitler
from a directionless loner

763
00:51:55,085 --> 00:51:57,749
to a hardened soldier.

764
00:51:57,750 --> 00:52:01,250
[Gas hissing, indistinct shouting]

765
00:52:02,750 --> 00:52:05,749
Hitler has escaped death twice...

766
00:52:05,750 --> 00:52:10,250
[Shouting indistinctly]

767
00:52:11,751 --> 00:52:15,084
Narrator: And it's left him a changed man.

768
00:52:15,085 --> 00:52:16,749
[Coughing]

769
00:52:16,750 --> 00:52:20,250
[Gasping]

770
00:52:37,750 --> 00:52:39,084
[Gunshot]

771
00:52:39,085 --> 00:52:42,749
Hitler didn't feel at this
time during the First World War

772
00:52:42,750 --> 00:52:44,749
that he was a man of destiny at all.

773
00:52:44,750 --> 00:52:46,251
[Gunshot]

774
00:52:46,252 --> 00:52:48,084
What he did feel was a sense of belonging

775
00:52:48,085 --> 00:52:49,749
and a sense of commitment,

776
00:52:49,750 --> 00:52:52,749
and that, I think, made him braver

777
00:52:52,750 --> 00:52:54,749
than he might otherwise have been.

778
00:52:54,750 --> 00:52:57,749
He felt he was fighting in
a really important cause,

779
00:52:57,750 --> 00:52:58,749
the cause of Germany.

780
00:52:58,750 --> 00:53:00,749
[Gunshot]

781
00:53:00,750 --> 00:53:04,127
Narrator: Hitler's ideology
takes root on the front lines.

782
00:53:05,252 --> 00:53:07,749
He begins to believe
in Germany's superiority

783
00:53:07,750 --> 00:53:10,749
over the Allies

784
00:53:10,750 --> 00:53:12,637
and is now certain he can withstand

785
00:53:12,638 --> 00:53:15,250
anything the Allied forces throw his way.

786
00:53:17,460 --> 00:53:18,749
<i>Gas!</i>

787
00:53:18,750 --> 00:53:21,749
[Intense percussive music]

788
00:53:21,750 --> 00:53:26,250
♪ ♪

789
00:53:32,750 --> 00:53:35,749
Narrator: The gas attacks are endless.

790
00:53:35,750 --> 00:53:39,250
To Hitler, they've become almost routine.

791
00:53:48,918 --> 00:53:52,250
But this time it's different.

792
00:53:56,709 --> 00:53:57,749
The Allies hit the Germans

793
00:53:57,750 --> 00:54:01,917
with a deadly new form of chemical warfare:

794
00:54:01,918 --> 00:54:03,822
Mustard gas.

795
00:54:04,491 --> 00:54:07,469
It lingers in the trenches for days.

796
00:54:07,750 --> 00:54:12,251
And attacks both the
respiratory system and the skin.

797
00:54:12,252 --> 00:54:14,749
Mustard gas affects the
central nervous system.

798
00:54:14,750 --> 00:54:18,749
It creates mustard-colored
blisters on the skin.

799
00:54:18,750 --> 00:54:19,749
It blinds people.

800
00:54:19,750 --> 00:54:21,749
It strips away the mucous membranes.

801
00:54:21,750 --> 00:54:25,749
It's incredibly painful and debilitating,

802
00:54:25,750 --> 00:54:27,749
and since it had no odor,

803
00:54:27,750 --> 00:54:29,749
by the time you realized
that you had inhaled it,

804
00:54:29,750 --> 00:54:32,250
and it was on your skin, it was too late.

805
00:54:43,750 --> 00:54:47,250
[Coughing]

806
00:55:29,750 --> 00:55:33,250
[Coughing]

807
00:55:38,374 --> 00:55:41,496
Narrator: After three years of bloody war,

808
00:55:41,497 --> 00:55:43,997
the stalemate in Europe has been broken.

809
00:55:46,497 --> 00:55:49,874
The United States has
joined the fighting...

810
00:55:51,497 --> 00:55:53,997
Giving Allied armies a needed boost...

811
00:55:55,497 --> 00:55:57,496
Fire!

812
00:55:57,497 --> 00:55:59,373
Pull back!

813
00:55:59,374 --> 00:56:02,496
Narrator: And driving the Germans
back to their original defensive line

814
00:56:02,497 --> 00:56:05,496
in northern France.

815
00:56:05,497 --> 00:56:08,496
But the German army remains powerful,

816
00:56:08,497 --> 00:56:11,874
meaning the Allies have to act fast.

817
00:56:18,497 --> 00:56:21,997
[Explosions]

818
00:56:26,999 --> 00:56:29,496
Brigadier General Douglas MacArthur

819
00:56:29,497 --> 00:56:32,874
is seeking every tactical advantage.

820
00:56:36,374 --> 00:56:38,496
Military leaders are human beings

821
00:56:38,497 --> 00:56:41,814
that are remarkably different
in personality and background.

822
00:56:42,522 --> 00:56:44,576
Every so often,

823
00:56:44,577 --> 00:56:46,496
someone crosses the constellation

824
00:56:46,497 --> 00:56:47,496
of military leaders

825
00:56:47,497 --> 00:56:49,496
a little bit like a shooting star,

826
00:56:49,497 --> 00:56:51,997
and Douglas MacArthur did that.

827
00:56:54,497 --> 00:56:57,496
Narrator: MacArthur learns
of a surveillance photograph

828
00:56:57,497 --> 00:56:59,496
of German trenches along
the Western front...

829
00:56:59,497 --> 00:57:01,373
[Camera shutter clicking]

830
00:57:01,374 --> 00:57:05,997
That reveals an undetected
gap in the German line.

831
00:57:09,497 --> 00:57:11,496
Where others see an unbreakable defense,

832
00:57:11,497 --> 00:57:15,997
MacArthur knows he can
exploit that weakness.

833
00:57:18,665 --> 00:57:21,496
Intelligence is essential,

834
00:57:21,497 --> 00:57:23,496
and the more you can get, the better.

835
00:57:23,497 --> 00:57:25,496
But at the end of the day,

836
00:57:25,497 --> 00:57:27,496
it's your instinct as a senior person.

837
00:57:27,497 --> 00:57:29,496
The reason we're wearing stars

838
00:57:29,497 --> 00:57:31,496
or have these elevated positions is,

839
00:57:31,497 --> 00:57:33,496
we have demonstrated over the years

840
00:57:33,497 --> 00:57:37,496
our ability to have an instinct that works.

841
00:57:37,497 --> 00:57:41,496
Narrator: MacArthur is determined
to break through the line

842
00:57:41,497 --> 00:57:43,997
and surround the Germans
in their trenches...

843
00:57:46,832 --> 00:57:49,496
Supported by George S. Patton

844
00:57:49,497 --> 00:57:51,997
and his Battalion of tanks.

845
00:57:56,497 --> 00:57:58,373
In the fall of 1918...

846
00:57:58,374 --> 00:58:00,496
Come on! Come on!

847
00:58:00,497 --> 00:58:04,496
Narrator: The Allies
launch an all-out attack

848
00:58:04,497 --> 00:58:06,154
in what will come to be known...

849
00:58:06,155 --> 00:58:07,496
Fire!

850
00:58:07,497 --> 00:58:09,951
Narrator: As the 100 days offensive.

851
00:58:09,952 --> 00:58:12,272
Boosted by MacArthur's men.

852
00:58:12,374 --> 00:58:13,496
And Patton's tanks...

853
00:58:13,497 --> 00:58:14,998
Get a move... move! Move!

854
00:58:14,999 --> 00:58:16,496
Narrator: The Allied armies

855
00:58:16,497 --> 00:58:18,496
become the most dominant fighting force

856
00:58:18,497 --> 00:58:20,496
the war has ever seen.

857
00:58:20,497 --> 00:58:21,997
Press forward!

858
00:58:24,497 --> 00:58:26,496
Both of 'em had big egos,

859
00:58:26,497 --> 00:58:28,496
but there's no doubt that both of them

860
00:58:28,497 --> 00:58:29,791
were brilliant on the battlefield.

861
00:58:29,792 --> 00:58:31,496
Go on, keep advancing!

862
00:58:31,497 --> 00:58:34,496
MacArthur was an extraordinarily talented

863
00:58:34,497 --> 00:58:36,496
and effective military leader.

864
00:58:36,497 --> 00:58:38,496
Fire!

865
00:58:38,497 --> 00:58:40,496
Patton, for what he was asked to do,

866
00:58:40,497 --> 00:58:43,496
which was trying to
break out of the trenches,

867
00:58:43,497 --> 00:58:45,997
there was probably nobody better.

868
00:58:46,999 --> 00:58:48,373
Move! Move!

869
00:58:48,374 --> 00:58:50,496
On, come on! Move!

870
00:58:50,497 --> 00:58:53,496
[Gunfire]

871
00:58:53,497 --> 00:58:54,496
Incoming!

872
00:58:54,497 --> 00:58:56,997
[Explosion]

873
00:58:59,497 --> 00:59:03,496
Move! Move! Move!

874
00:59:03,497 --> 00:59:06,997
[Gunfire]

875
00:59:13,497 --> 00:59:15,496
Narrator: The Allies relentlessly attack

876
00:59:15,497 --> 00:59:18,997
the German line from every direction.

877
00:59:22,374 --> 00:59:23,997
[Gunshot]

878
00:59:25,497 --> 00:59:27,496
[Gunshot]

879
00:59:27,497 --> 00:59:30,997
[Explosions, gunfire]

880
00:59:33,999 --> 00:59:36,496
Move! Move! Move! Move!

881
00:59:36,497 --> 00:59:37,496
Come on! Come on!

882
00:59:37,497 --> 00:59:39,664
Let's go! Let's go! Let's go!

883
00:59:39,665 --> 00:59:42,496
[Dramatic orchestral music]

884
00:59:42,497 --> 00:59:44,496
Narrator: After months of fighting,

885
00:59:44,497 --> 00:59:46,496
the Allies finally break through...

886
00:59:46,497 --> 00:59:49,496
[Gunshot]

887
00:59:49,497 --> 00:59:52,496
Putting the mighty German army on the run.

888
00:59:52,497 --> 00:59:54,373
[Gunshot]

889
00:59:54,374 --> 00:59:55,664
[Indistinct shouting]

890
00:59:55,665 --> 00:59:57,997
[Grunting]

891
00:59:58,497 --> 01:00:01,496
Narrator: Finally, with no other option,

892
01:00:01,497 --> 01:00:03,831
tens of thousands of German soldiers...

893
01:00:03,832 --> 01:00:05,998
Do it now!

894
01:00:05,999 --> 01:00:07,496
Narrator: Lay down their guns...

895
01:00:07,497 --> 01:00:09,496
Hands up!

896
01:00:09,497 --> 01:00:10,997
Narrator: And surrender.

897
01:00:14,665 --> 01:00:16,496
You look at the great leaders.

898
01:00:16,497 --> 01:00:18,496
These were men who understood

899
01:00:18,497 --> 01:00:21,496
the most important resource
they had available to them

900
01:00:21,497 --> 01:00:22,496
to fight a war...

901
01:00:22,497 --> 01:00:24,373
not the weapons, not the planes,

902
01:00:24,374 --> 01:00:25,496
not the tanks.

903
01:00:25,497 --> 01:00:28,496
It's the soldiers who get it done,

904
01:00:28,497 --> 01:00:30,497
and leadership is all about
inspiring your soldiers

905
01:00:30,498 --> 01:00:32,997
to achieve a decisive win.

906
01:00:40,497 --> 01:00:43,696
Narrator: After four years
of continuous fighting

907
01:00:43,993 --> 01:00:47,170
and 37 million casualties,

908
01:00:47,171 --> 01:00:50,661
the two sides agree to a cease fire.

909
01:00:54,497 --> 01:00:58,389
When the world is shaking
and rearranging itself

910
01:00:58,390 --> 01:01:01,930
as it does after a great
events, like the end of a war.

911
01:01:02,207 --> 01:01:04,647
There are a whole range
of different emotions.

912
01:01:04,648 --> 01:01:07,496
The first is exhilaration,
a very personal feeling,

913
01:01:07,497 --> 01:01:09,496
exhilaration at being part of an event

914
01:01:09,497 --> 01:01:11,373
that is changing the world,

915
01:01:11,374 --> 01:01:13,496
and there's never much time to look back.

916
01:01:13,497 --> 01:01:15,997
There's always a lot to look forward to.

917
01:01:21,175 --> 01:01:22,496
Narrator: While most of the world

918
01:01:22,497 --> 01:01:26,496
celebrates the end of the fighting,

919
01:01:26,497 --> 01:01:29,496
some deep in the heart of Germany

920
01:01:29,497 --> 01:01:32,997
refuse to accept defeat.

921
01:01:36,497 --> 01:01:39,496
Hitler was wounded in the gas attack

922
01:01:39,497 --> 01:01:42,496
at the very end of the war,

923
01:01:42,497 --> 01:01:45,997
and he was then hospitalized,
temporarily blinded.

924
01:01:47,497 --> 01:01:49,496
That our people will be losing the war

925
01:01:49,497 --> 01:01:52,997
against the Western armies...

926
01:01:54,999 --> 01:01:56,831
While he was in hospital,

927
01:01:56,832 --> 01:02:00,998
he was then told that Germany
had lost the First World War,

928
01:02:00,999 --> 01:02:03,496
and that's a crucial turning point

929
01:02:03,497 --> 01:02:06,206
in Hitler's life.

930
01:02:06,207 --> 01:02:07,664
In Hitler's worldview,

931
01:02:07,665 --> 01:02:10,210
it was always, um,

932
01:02:10,412 --> 01:02:12,280
dead or alive,

933
01:02:13,207 --> 01:02:15,556
win or total defeat.

934
01:02:15,557 --> 01:02:19,496
For him, surrender was something un-German.

935
01:02:19,497 --> 01:02:22,636
You are a coward,
somehow, if you surrender.

936
01:02:22,637 --> 01:02:24,664
[Tense music]

937
01:02:24,665 --> 01:02:37,496
♪ ♪

938
01:02:37,497 --> 01:02:40,874
Hitler took the surrender personally...

939
01:02:42,497 --> 01:02:46,997
A personal destructive blow to himself.

940
01:02:48,497 --> 01:02:52,496
He also took it as a mission,

941
01:02:52,497 --> 01:02:54,496
a mission in life

942
01:02:54,497 --> 01:02:58,997
to avenge and rectify the surrender.

943
01:03:07,914 --> 01:03:12,913
Narrator: After four long and bloody years

944
01:03:12,914 --> 01:03:16,913
and 37 million casualties,

945
01:03:16,914 --> 01:03:19,913
the United States and the Allies

946
01:03:19,914 --> 01:03:23,913
have finally claimed victory,

947
01:03:23,914 --> 01:03:27,705
forcing Germany to surrender.

948
01:03:36,624 --> 01:03:38,913
But while the fighting has stopped,

949
01:03:38,914 --> 01:03:41,415
the pressure is now on the Allied leaders

950
01:03:41,416 --> 01:03:43,913
to come to an agreement

951
01:03:43,914 --> 01:03:47,291
preventing war from
ever breaking out again.

952
01:03:50,291 --> 01:03:52,413
As negotiations to secure the peace

953
01:03:52,414 --> 01:03:56,413
get underway in France,

954
01:03:56,414 --> 01:03:59,581
massive crowds greet the world leaders...

955
01:03:59,582 --> 01:04:03,413
[Cheers and applause]

956
01:04:03,414 --> 01:04:05,581
Including United States President

957
01:04:05,582 --> 01:04:07,413
Woodrow Wilson.

958
01:04:07,414 --> 01:04:11,413
Woodrow Wilson was the first
President of the United States

959
01:04:11,414 --> 01:04:13,290
to spend anywhere near six months

960
01:04:13,291 --> 01:04:14,413
outside this country,

961
01:04:14,414 --> 01:04:17,413
and he felt that for
him to send anyone else

962
01:04:17,414 --> 01:04:19,290
to negotiate the peace,

963
01:04:19,291 --> 01:04:21,413
it would not have been as well done.

964
01:04:21,414 --> 01:04:24,915
Wilson said, "Whatever happens
with the settlement of this war,

965
01:04:24,916 --> 01:04:27,501
"if it goes well, give me credit.

966
01:04:27,502 --> 01:04:29,914
If it doesn't, blame me."

967
01:04:35,414 --> 01:04:39,290
Narrator: The leaders gather
at the Palace of Versailles.

968
01:04:39,291 --> 01:04:43,581
But one country not invited
to the table is Germany.

969
01:04:43,582 --> 01:04:47,413
Gentlemen, please, please sit down.

970
01:04:47,414 --> 01:04:50,413
If we can start by considering the points

971
01:04:50,414 --> 01:04:54,341
before we discuss any of
the individual ideas...

972
01:04:54,342 --> 01:04:55,839
The main thing

973
01:04:55,840 --> 01:04:57,913
that Woodrow Wilson wanted
to accomplish at Versailles

974
01:04:57,914 --> 01:05:00,615
was defanging Germany,

975
01:05:00,616 --> 01:05:04,756
not allowing them to develop
a huge war machine again.

976
01:05:04,757 --> 01:05:08,661
This was what the victors
all wanted to see happen.

977
01:05:08,662 --> 01:05:11,661
Narrator: But as negotiations get underway,

978
01:05:11,662 --> 01:05:13,661
Wilson quickly realizes

979
01:05:13,662 --> 01:05:16,128
that each country has come to the table

980
01:05:16,129 --> 01:05:17,558
with their own agenda.

981
01:05:17,662 --> 01:05:21,538
There were these national leaders

982
01:05:21,539 --> 01:05:23,996
who had different views of what they wanted

983
01:05:23,997 --> 01:05:27,371
out of the Paris peace conference.

984
01:05:27,372 --> 01:05:28,661
They had led their countries

985
01:05:28,662 --> 01:05:33,538
through this brutal, bloody, long war,

986
01:05:33,539 --> 01:05:35,538
and Wilson waltzes in with the Americans

987
01:05:35,539 --> 01:05:36,661
just at the end.

988
01:05:36,662 --> 01:05:40,538
So they had to listen to him,

989
01:05:40,539 --> 01:05:43,661
and Wilson could be kind of persuasive...

990
01:05:43,662 --> 01:05:45,661
but not that persuasive.

991
01:05:45,662 --> 01:05:49,084
Narrator: As negotiations
drag on for months,

992
01:05:49,085 --> 01:05:53,084
the talks fall apart,

993
01:05:53,085 --> 01:05:55,586
and one Allied nation

994
01:05:55,587 --> 01:05:59,084
feels completely cut
out of the negotiations.

995
01:05:59,085 --> 01:06:02,726
Japan entered the war in 1914,

996
01:06:03,413 --> 01:06:05,523
contributing thousands of troops

997
01:06:05,524 --> 01:06:08,024
and millions of dollars to the war effort.

998
01:06:10,524 --> 01:06:13,025
They come to Versailles with one goal:

999
01:06:13,026 --> 01:06:14,691
To be treated equally.

1000
01:06:14,692 --> 01:06:17,524
But Allied leaders completely ignore Japan

1001
01:06:17,525 --> 01:06:20,523
throughout the proceedings,

1002
01:06:20,524 --> 01:06:22,523
and for Japan,

1003
01:06:22,524 --> 01:06:24,523
it's the ultimate insult.

1004
01:06:24,524 --> 01:06:26,502
The Japanese, who'd
been on the winning side,

1005
01:06:26,503 --> 01:06:29,088
get this slap at the peace conference.

1006
01:06:29,524 --> 01:06:33,858
So the Japanese became alienated

1007
01:06:33,859 --> 01:06:38,523
from the United States and
from the Western powers,

1008
01:06:38,524 --> 01:06:41,523
and it was a fairly
straight line from there

1009
01:06:41,524 --> 01:06:43,523
to the belief that,

1010
01:06:43,524 --> 01:06:45,662
"if we're gonna get any respect,

1011
01:06:45,663 --> 01:06:48,629
it's going to be by fighting
are way to respect.

1012
01:06:55,524 --> 01:06:57,523
Narrator: The attention shifts

1013
01:06:57,524 --> 01:07:00,523
from Wilson's plan for a lasting peace

1014
01:07:00,524 --> 01:07:04,523
to a plan focused on punishing Germany,

1015
01:07:04,524 --> 01:07:05,691
forcing them to pay

1016
01:07:05,692 --> 01:07:08,523
for the devastation they've caused.

1017
01:07:08,524 --> 01:07:11,523
The reparations that
were demanded of Germany

1018
01:07:11,524 --> 01:07:13,524
were astronomical.

1019
01:07:13,525 --> 01:07:15,523
It was a matter of,

1020
01:07:15,524 --> 01:07:18,364
"we're gonna squeeze as much
out of Germany as we can."

1021
01:07:18,365 --> 01:07:20,532
Well, there were some on the American side

1022
01:07:20,533 --> 01:07:24,684
who said, "we are making
the next war inevitable."

1023
01:07:24,685 --> 01:07:26,684
Wilson worked against that.

1024
01:07:26,685 --> 01:07:31,186
Wilson wanted a somewhat
more reasonable peace,

1025
01:07:31,187 --> 01:07:35,684
and he wanted the Germans
to feel that they had a stake

1026
01:07:35,685 --> 01:07:38,685
in the continuation of
the Versailles system.

1027
01:07:38,686 --> 01:07:42,684
The problem with the treaty
as it was finalized was,

1028
01:07:42,685 --> 01:07:44,684
Germany had no stake in that system.

1029
01:07:44,685 --> 01:07:47,685
It had every interest in
overturning the system.

1030
01:07:47,686 --> 01:07:49,685
Narrator: Despite Wilson's best efforts,

1031
01:07:49,686 --> 01:07:52,684
he is unable to convince the other Allies

1032
01:07:52,685 --> 01:07:55,185
to buy into his plan for peace.

1033
01:07:56,685 --> 01:08:00,394
After six months of intense negotiations,

1034
01:08:00,395 --> 01:08:03,185
the Allies finally have a treaty.

1035
01:08:05,395 --> 01:08:06,684
But the final agreement

1036
01:08:06,685 --> 01:08:09,684
is far from the fair and equitable plan

1037
01:08:09,685 --> 01:08:12,561
Wilson had originally hoped for.

1038
01:08:12,562 --> 01:08:14,684
The losers, Germany principally,

1039
01:08:14,685 --> 01:08:15,684
they were there.

1040
01:08:15,685 --> 01:08:17,684
They didn't get to speak.

1041
01:08:17,685 --> 01:08:19,684
They weren't asked to contribute.

1042
01:08:19,685 --> 01:08:21,684
They were basically...

1043
01:08:21,685 --> 01:08:24,561
they had a gun put at
their heads figuratively...

1044
01:08:24,562 --> 01:08:25,684
almost literally...

1045
01:08:25,685 --> 01:08:27,684
and said, "you're gonna
sign on the dotted line."

1046
01:08:27,685 --> 01:08:29,852
It was very much a Victor's peace.

1047
01:08:29,853 --> 01:08:32,684
The victors dictated
the terms of the peace.

1048
01:08:32,685 --> 01:08:36,185
They made out like bandits.

1049
01:08:42,685 --> 01:08:45,684
Narrator: Europe is finally at peace.

1050
01:08:45,685 --> 01:08:49,394
But while most of the world celebrates,

1051
01:08:49,395 --> 01:08:51,321
Germany is ordered to pay the Allies

1052
01:08:51,322 --> 01:08:53,283
over 80 Billion dollars.

1053
01:08:53,685 --> 01:08:57,684
The modern equivalent
of nearly 1/2 a trillion dollars,

1054
01:08:57,685 --> 01:09:00,892
a debt they won't pay off until 2010.

1055
01:09:01,435 --> 01:09:03,684
As a result,

1056
01:09:03,685 --> 01:09:05,684
the government quickly goes bankrupt,

1057
01:09:05,685 --> 01:09:08,185
leaving millions of Germans impoverished.

1058
01:09:12,685 --> 01:09:13,684
The economic devastation

1059
01:09:13,685 --> 01:09:18,185
completely transforms the
country and its people.

1060
01:09:19,685 --> 01:09:21,852
Germany immediately is struggling

1061
01:09:21,853 --> 01:09:23,684
with a question of survival.

1062
01:09:23,685 --> 01:09:24,685
For ordinary Germans,

1063
01:09:24,686 --> 01:09:27,828
the war did not end in November 1918.

1064
01:09:28,057 --> 01:09:30,137
For ordinary Germans the
battle for survival,

1065
01:09:30,138 --> 01:09:31,684
the daily struggle for food,

1066
01:09:31,685 --> 01:09:33,684
the effort to find shoes and clothing

1067
01:09:33,685 --> 01:09:36,185
stretched on into the 1920s.

1068
01:09:37,686 --> 01:09:41,019
Narrator: As the anger
and starvation spread,

1069
01:09:41,020 --> 01:09:43,186
tensions rise throughout the country.

1070
01:09:43,187 --> 01:09:45,186
[Indistinct shouting]

1071
01:09:45,187 --> 01:09:48,684
Germany is in a state of near Civil War.

1072
01:09:48,685 --> 01:09:50,561
The left and the right

1073
01:09:50,562 --> 01:09:52,394
are fighting with each
other in the streets.

1074
01:09:52,395 --> 01:09:54,186
Paramilitary groups clash.

1075
01:09:54,187 --> 01:09:58,185
Germany is a country
divided against itself.

1076
01:10:01,685 --> 01:10:05,684
When World War I came to an end,

1077
01:10:05,685 --> 01:10:08,382
this is not a treaty.

1078
01:10:08,383 --> 01:10:12,883
This is an armistice that'll
probably last 20 years...

1079
01:10:15,718 --> 01:10:19,760
Meaning we have not really
defeated the German spirit.

1080
01:10:21,885 --> 01:10:25,883
We have not really solved this problem.

1081
01:10:33,609 --> 01:10:37,608
Narrator: With the fighting stopped,

1082
01:10:37,609 --> 01:10:41,109
the treaty for peace
is signed at Versailles.

1083
01:10:42,319 --> 01:10:44,608
[Cheers and applause]

1084
01:10:44,609 --> 01:10:47,608
And for the first time in over four years,

1085
01:10:47,609 --> 01:10:51,318
Europe is at peace.

1086
01:10:51,319 --> 01:10:54,608
While celebrations erupt around the world,

1087
01:10:54,609 --> 01:10:58,110
Germany is in a state of unrest,

1088
01:10:58,111 --> 01:11:02,109
and many are convinced
that the peace won't hold.

1089
01:11:09,609 --> 01:11:13,109
Among them is Winston Churchill.

1090
01:11:14,944 --> 01:11:18,110
Having just returned to
England from the front lines,

1091
01:11:18,111 --> 01:11:21,776
he sets out to reestablish
his political career,

1092
01:11:21,777 --> 01:11:26,318
narrowly winning reelection
to his old seat in parliament.

1093
01:11:26,319 --> 01:11:28,608
There were a lot of doubts about Churchill.

1094
01:11:28,609 --> 01:11:31,318
He seemed erratic in his judgments.

1095
01:11:31,319 --> 01:11:33,943
His decision in respect
to the Gallipoli campaign

1096
01:11:33,944 --> 01:11:37,608
had disastrous consequences.

1097
01:11:37,609 --> 01:11:41,110
But it was in war that he proved
his leadership credentials,

1098
01:11:41,111 --> 01:11:44,609
and that's what transformed him.

1099
01:11:44,610 --> 01:11:46,608
Narrator: Churchill returns to government

1100
01:11:46,609 --> 01:11:50,444
convinced the German
threat hasn't gone away.

1101
01:11:53,609 --> 01:11:56,608
[Whistle blowing intermittently]

1102
01:11:56,609 --> 01:11:59,608
After leading his troops
to victory in France,

1103
01:11:59,609 --> 01:12:01,608
Brigadier General Douglas MacArthur

1104
01:12:01,609 --> 01:12:03,608
is given one of the most
prestigious positions

1105
01:12:03,609 --> 01:12:04,608
in the armed forces...

1106
01:12:04,609 --> 01:12:07,082
- Will you be late again?
- No, sir!

1107
01:12:07,083 --> 01:12:10,668
Superintendent of the Military
Academy at West Point.

1108
01:12:10,709 --> 01:12:12,943
Where he immediately gets to work

1109
01:12:12,944 --> 01:12:15,485
preparing American soldiers for combat

1110
01:12:15,486 --> 01:12:18,109
in case the peace fails.

1111
01:12:21,609 --> 01:12:23,609
240 miles away

1112
01:12:23,610 --> 01:12:26,608
at his tank academy in
Camp Meade, Maryland,

1113
01:12:26,609 --> 01:12:28,608
Colonel George S. Patton...

1114
01:12:28,609 --> 01:12:30,110
Ready!

1115
01:12:30,111 --> 01:12:31,608
Narrator: Is also training

1116
01:12:31,609 --> 01:12:33,608
the next generation of American soldiers.

1117
01:12:33,609 --> 01:12:35,608
Aim!

1118
01:12:35,609 --> 01:12:37,608
Narrator: And like MacArthur,

1119
01:12:37,609 --> 01:12:41,608
he's betting the cease-fire won't last.

1120
01:12:41,609 --> 01:12:43,608
[Gunshots]

1121
01:12:43,609 --> 01:12:45,608
- Fire!
- [Gunshots]

1122
01:12:45,609 --> 01:12:47,608
Fire!

1123
01:12:47,609 --> 01:12:50,109
- Fire!
- [Gunshots]

1124
01:12:51,111 --> 01:12:52,609
[Bells tolling]

1125
01:12:52,610 --> 01:12:54,608
Narrator: In Italy,

1126
01:12:54,609 --> 01:12:56,608
one man sees the end of fighting

1127
01:12:56,609 --> 01:12:59,608
as an opportunity.

1128
01:12:59,609 --> 01:13:02,608
Benito Mussolini returns to his job

1129
01:13:02,609 --> 01:13:03,988
as a newspaper journalist.

1130
01:13:03,989 --> 01:13:06,608
But the country he fought to protect

1131
01:13:06,609 --> 01:13:08,943
is now in disarray.

1132
01:13:08,944 --> 01:13:11,608
The Italians came out of
the war on the winning side

1133
01:13:11,609 --> 01:13:15,608
but failed to gain the territory
they had expected to gain,

1134
01:13:15,609 --> 01:13:18,608
and there's a sense of outrage about this

1135
01:13:18,609 --> 01:13:19,943
amongst Italian nationalists,

1136
01:13:19,944 --> 01:13:23,608
a sense almost that Italy has lost the war

1137
01:13:23,609 --> 01:13:27,109
despite being on the winning side.

1138
01:13:27,609 --> 01:13:29,608
Narrator: Mussolini uses his newspaper

1139
01:13:29,609 --> 01:13:32,110
to convey his view of a new Italy,

1140
01:13:32,111 --> 01:13:34,608
that under a strong leader
the country can regain

1141
01:13:34,609 --> 01:13:37,608
the glory of the Roman empire.

1142
01:13:37,609 --> 01:13:40,109
He believes he can be that leader...

1143
01:13:42,111 --> 01:13:45,109
The man who returns Italy to greatness.

1144
01:13:49,777 --> 01:13:52,871
He soon brings his
anti-government views...

1145
01:13:54,362 --> 01:13:56,251
to a new medium...

1146
01:13:56,609 --> 01:13:58,608
radio.

1147
01:13:58,609 --> 01:14:00,608
We have actually been at war

1148
01:14:00,609 --> 01:14:03,608
since we lifted the flag of our revolution

1149
01:14:03,609 --> 01:14:08,608
which was then defended by a handful of men

1150
01:14:08,609 --> 01:14:11,608
against the masonic, democratic,

1151
01:14:11,609 --> 01:14:13,986
capitalistic world.

1152
01:14:14,609 --> 01:14:17,318
Mussolini was a man of strong words.

1153
01:14:17,319 --> 01:14:19,608
He liked the idea of overthrowing

1154
01:14:19,609 --> 01:14:21,608
existing institutions.

1155
01:14:21,609 --> 01:14:25,109
He favored the use of violence to do this.

1156
01:14:27,609 --> 01:14:30,608
Narrator: To make his vision a reality,

1157
01:14:30,609 --> 01:14:35,485
Mussolini forms a band of
disgruntled former soldiers

1158
01:14:35,486 --> 01:14:37,608
called the Blackshirts

1159
01:14:37,609 --> 01:14:41,608
who terrorize his political opponents

1160
01:14:41,609 --> 01:14:45,109
and begin preparing
for an armed revolution.

1161
01:14:46,609 --> 01:14:47,608
In a matter of months,

1162
01:14:47,609 --> 01:14:50,608
Mussolini has launched a movement

1163
01:14:50,609 --> 01:14:54,109
that is about to change the fate of Italy.

1164
01:15:05,610 --> 01:15:08,608
Lance Corporal Adolf Hitler.

1165
01:15:08,609 --> 01:15:10,608
Sir.

1166
01:15:10,609 --> 01:15:13,608
Sit down.

1167
01:15:13,609 --> 01:15:15,608
- So you're looking for work.
- Yes, sir.

1168
01:15:15,609 --> 01:15:16,608
I am ready for duty.

1169
01:15:16,609 --> 01:15:18,609
I understand.

1170
01:15:18,610 --> 01:15:22,608
Unfortunately, I have nothing.

1171
01:15:22,609 --> 01:15:23,608
Nothing?

1172
01:15:23,609 --> 01:15:25,608
There is no work.

1173
01:15:25,609 --> 01:15:28,608
The war is over.

1174
01:15:28,609 --> 01:15:32,608
There has to be something.

1175
01:15:32,609 --> 01:15:36,109
After all I've done,
after all I've given...

1176
01:15:39,777 --> 01:15:42,608
There is a new political group in town:

1177
01:15:42,609 --> 01:15:44,609
The German Workers' party.

1178
01:15:44,610 --> 01:15:47,608
We need to find out more about them

1179
01:15:47,609 --> 01:15:50,608
and what their intentions are.

1180
01:15:50,609 --> 01:15:54,109
- Yes, sir.
- Try to not stand out.

1181
01:16:00,488 --> 01:16:02,608
The Versailles Treaty caused
the economic conditions

1182
01:16:02,609 --> 01:16:06,608
which gave rise to extremism.

1183
01:16:06,609 --> 01:16:09,608
You find in history that
when an economy is terrible,

1184
01:16:09,609 --> 01:16:11,608
it gives rise to all kinds

1185
01:16:11,609 --> 01:16:16,109
of different extremist organizations.

1186
01:16:21,944 --> 01:16:24,608
Narrator: Hitler is assigned to infiltrate

1187
01:16:24,609 --> 01:16:26,943
the German Workers' party,

1188
01:16:26,944 --> 01:16:29,608
one of many anti-government organizations

1189
01:16:29,609 --> 01:16:32,109
that have formed in the wake of the treaty.

1190
01:16:33,111 --> 01:16:35,110
[Door creaks]

1191
01:16:38,609 --> 01:16:42,110
For months, he attends secret meetings

1192
01:16:42,111 --> 01:16:45,110
held at undisclosed locations
throughout the country.

1193
01:16:46,609 --> 01:16:49,819
They signed away our army.

1194
01:16:51,111 --> 01:16:55,109
The Versailles Treaty is not my treaty.

1195
01:16:56,609 --> 01:16:58,608
It was as if nothing had happened,

1196
01:16:58,609 --> 01:17:03,109
as if we are forgotten.

1197
01:17:05,319 --> 01:17:07,608
Narrator: But Hitler soon realizes

1198
01:17:07,609 --> 01:17:09,608
they are radical nationalists

1199
01:17:09,609 --> 01:17:12,608
intensely loyal to the fatherland,

1200
01:17:12,609 --> 01:17:15,484
and many of them harbor extremist views

1201
01:17:15,485 --> 01:17:17,496
of German superiority.

1202
01:17:18,609 --> 01:17:22,110
Views that are no different from his own.

1203
01:17:22,111 --> 01:17:24,608
There was never really an effort

1204
01:17:24,609 --> 01:17:26,608
to deal with all the damage

1205
01:17:26,609 --> 01:17:29,109
that had occurred during World War I.

1206
01:17:31,609 --> 01:17:34,318
The failure to do that

1207
01:17:34,319 --> 01:17:36,608
I think is what ultimately
produced the seeds

1208
01:17:36,609 --> 01:17:40,110
for Hitler and Nazism.

1209
01:17:41,609 --> 01:17:45,110
Germany as a whole is dead.

1210
01:17:46,610 --> 01:17:50,109
It has nothing left in its heart.

1211
01:17:51,609 --> 01:17:54,608
There are riots on the streets.

1212
01:17:54,609 --> 01:17:58,109
There is no Germany left to fight for.

1213
01:17:59,486 --> 01:18:03,110
Germany must break apart.

1214
01:18:03,111 --> 01:18:07,608
It is only through this
that we can survive.

1215
01:18:07,609 --> 01:18:08,609
No Germany?

1216
01:18:08,610 --> 01:18:11,608
Yes, there's nothing left to fight for.

1217
01:18:11,609 --> 01:18:13,608
"There's nothing left to fight for"

1218
01:18:13,609 --> 01:18:15,609
are the famous last words of every turncoat

1219
01:18:15,610 --> 01:18:18,776
in the history of warfare.

1220
01:18:18,777 --> 01:18:22,608
The weak among us turn to such excuses

1221
01:18:22,609 --> 01:18:24,608
and abandon our pride and hope

1222
01:18:24,609 --> 01:18:26,318
when it is only unity

1223
01:18:26,319 --> 01:18:28,611
that separates the
victors from the defeated.

1224
01:18:29,609 --> 01:18:32,608
Clearly you have stopped fighting.

1225
01:18:32,609 --> 01:18:36,608
But we are still fighting
Germany's great war, our war,

1226
01:18:36,609 --> 01:18:39,608
for what we deserve:

1227
01:18:39,609 --> 01:18:42,318
A united Germany,

1228
01:18:42,319 --> 01:18:45,109
a strong, proud Germany.

1229
01:18:45,609 --> 01:18:49,608
Germany is a sleeping giant,

1230
01:18:49,609 --> 01:18:51,608
and once we rid our nation

1231
01:18:51,609 --> 01:18:53,609
of the spineless frauds among us

1232
01:18:53,610 --> 01:18:55,776
and alongside the criminals of Versailles,

1233
01:18:55,777 --> 01:18:59,608
we will once again know greatness.

1234
01:18:59,609 --> 01:19:03,109
[Applause]

1235
01:19:27,955 --> 01:19:31,954
Narrator: After four years of war,

1236
01:19:31,955 --> 01:19:33,954
a tenuous peace holds.

1237
01:19:33,955 --> 01:19:36,954
[Birds cawing]

1238
01:19:36,955 --> 01:19:40,455
But anger and resentment are spreading...

1239
01:19:42,607 --> 01:19:45,716
and shots are about to be fired again.

1240
01:19:45,955 --> 01:19:49,623
[Applause]

1241
01:19:57,955 --> 01:20:01,954
Adolf Hitler leaves the German army

1242
01:20:01,955 --> 01:20:03,954
to fully devote himself

1243
01:20:03,955 --> 01:20:06,455
to the anti-government Workers Party.

1244
01:20:07,955 --> 01:20:10,954
Our Germany is dead,
and you have conspired...

1245
01:20:10,955 --> 01:20:13,954
Narrator: His popularity and fiery rhetoric

1246
01:20:13,955 --> 01:20:15,954
make him stand out in the group.

1247
01:20:15,955 --> 01:20:18,954
You have bled her with your corruption.

1248
01:20:18,955 --> 01:20:22,400
Narrator: And he's promoted
to the head of propaganda.

1249
01:20:26,955 --> 01:20:30,954
We will call ourselves the
National Socialist Party!

1250
01:20:30,955 --> 01:20:33,954
[Cheers and applause]

1251
01:20:33,955 --> 01:20:35,954
Narrator: Under Hitler's leadership,

1252
01:20:35,955 --> 01:20:37,954
membership in the National Socialist Party

1253
01:20:37,955 --> 01:20:40,573
quickly expands

1254
01:20:40,955 --> 01:20:45,077
as Hitler experiences his
first taste of real power.

1255
01:20:49,955 --> 01:20:51,954
There are many reports from fairly early on

1256
01:20:51,955 --> 01:20:54,954
about Hitler's charisma as a speaker,

1257
01:20:54,955 --> 01:20:57,954
and he gradually came to realize

1258
01:20:57,955 --> 01:21:00,954
that he was indeed a powerful speaker...

1259
01:21:00,955 --> 01:21:02,955
far more powerful than
anyone else around...

1260
01:21:02,956 --> 01:21:07,954
and began to use that as an asset.

1261
01:21:07,955 --> 01:21:10,954
Narrator: To cast all
Germany under his spell,

1262
01:21:10,955 --> 01:21:11,954
Hitler needs an image

1263
01:21:11,955 --> 01:21:15,954
that will burn into the minds of millions.

1264
01:21:15,955 --> 01:21:17,954
Nowadays we'd call it a logo of course.

1265
01:21:17,955 --> 01:21:19,955
It was designed personally by Hitler,

1266
01:21:19,956 --> 01:21:21,954
and it may be that he put

1267
01:21:21,955 --> 01:21:24,954
some of his artistic impulses into this.

1268
01:21:24,955 --> 01:21:28,954
The essential part of it
ultimately went back to India,

1269
01:21:28,955 --> 01:21:33,954
but it was taken up as a symbol
of racism and anti-semitism

1270
01:21:33,955 --> 01:21:35,954
combined with the red
background for socialism

1271
01:21:35,955 --> 01:21:37,954
and the red, white, and black colors

1272
01:21:37,955 --> 01:21:40,455
for the old Kaiser Reich.

1273
01:21:58,754 --> 01:22:02,954
Narrator: While Hitler is still in
the early stages of his revolution,

1274
01:22:02,955 --> 01:22:07,954
Benito Mussolini has already
amassed an army of followers

1275
01:22:07,955 --> 01:22:11,455
and is ready to take Italy by force.

1276
01:22:18,955 --> 01:22:22,571
For seven days in October of 1922

1277
01:22:22,572 --> 01:22:26,071
in a massive show of his popularity.

1278
01:22:27,955 --> 01:22:32,957
Mussolini leads a march of
30,000 Blackshirts into Rome.

1279
01:22:34,665 --> 01:22:35,954
With the people behind him,

1280
01:22:35,955 --> 01:22:39,954
Mussolini and the Blackshirts
storm the Royal Palace,

1281
01:22:39,955 --> 01:22:44,455
forcing the King of Italy to hand
over control of the government.

1282
01:22:46,955 --> 01:22:50,954
Mussolini came to power in Italy in 1922.

1283
01:22:50,955 --> 01:22:53,954
His successful march on Rome

1284
01:22:53,955 --> 01:22:59,954
was eased by the process of
expanding ego and adulation

1285
01:22:59,955 --> 01:23:02,954
by the people around Mussolini

1286
01:23:02,955 --> 01:23:04,954
and then eventually most
of the public opinion

1287
01:23:04,955 --> 01:23:07,455
in the country.

1288
01:23:08,955 --> 01:23:12,455
This is a dangerous process.

1289
01:23:14,832 --> 01:23:15,954
Narrator: In just months,

1290
01:23:15,955 --> 01:23:18,954
Mussolini has been transformed
from newspaper journalist

1291
01:23:18,955 --> 01:23:22,455
to the most powerful man in Italy.

1292
01:23:27,955 --> 01:23:30,954
600 miles to the north,

1293
01:23:30,955 --> 01:23:35,831
Adolf Hitler is watching
everything Mussolini has done,

1294
01:23:35,832 --> 01:23:40,455
and he wants that same
ultimate power for himself.

1295
01:23:40,955 --> 01:23:43,455
So he amasses an army of his own.

1296
01:23:44,955 --> 01:23:47,664
Hitler does seem early to have been

1297
01:23:47,665 --> 01:23:49,715
very impressed by Mussolini

1298
01:23:49,716 --> 01:23:51,954
and indeed by the march on Rome.

1299
01:23:51,955 --> 01:23:53,949
His rise to power was modeled on what

1300
01:23:53,950 --> 01:23:56,885
the Italian Fascists had done in Italy.

1301
01:23:57,734 --> 01:24:00,644
On November 8, 1923,

1302
01:24:00,955 --> 01:24:05,954
Hitler leads the Nazis
into a Munich beer hall

1303
01:24:05,955 --> 01:24:08,455
where top government officials are meeting.

1304
01:24:08,955 --> 01:24:12,455
[Indistinct chatter]

1305
01:24:14,832 --> 01:24:16,954
[Gunshots]

1306
01:24:16,955 --> 01:24:18,954
Germany is dead,

1307
01:24:18,955 --> 01:24:22,122
and you have conspired to kill her!

1308
01:24:22,123 --> 01:24:24,955
You have crushed her
with your incompetence.

1309
01:24:24,956 --> 01:24:27,954
You have bled her with your corruption.

1310
01:24:27,955 --> 01:24:31,954
[Gun cocking]

1311
01:24:31,955 --> 01:24:33,954
You have profaned her by consorting

1312
01:24:33,955 --> 01:24:35,954
with degenerate peoples.

1313
01:24:35,955 --> 01:24:37,954
No more!

1314
01:24:37,955 --> 01:24:40,455
The revolution has begun!

1315
01:24:44,955 --> 01:24:46,954
Join us now

1316
01:24:46,955 --> 01:24:50,455
as we give birth to a new Germany!

1317
01:24:52,955 --> 01:24:56,954
You watch him, and you
think of how Adolf Hitler

1318
01:24:56,955 --> 01:24:57,954
was able to do that,

1319
01:24:57,955 --> 01:25:01,954
to get other people to follow him.

1320
01:25:01,955 --> 01:25:04,954
I think it was partly because

1321
01:25:04,955 --> 01:25:07,732
he could persuade people that
that was a good thing to do

1322
01:25:07,733 --> 01:25:10,455
and partly because people
were intimidated by him.

1323
01:25:17,955 --> 01:25:19,954
Narrator: After storming the beer hall,

1324
01:25:19,955 --> 01:25:23,954
Hitler leads the Nazis into the streets

1325
01:25:23,955 --> 01:25:26,455
to take the city by force.

1326
01:25:29,955 --> 01:25:31,831
But unlike in Italy,

1327
01:25:31,832 --> 01:25:33,954
the German police are prepared.

1328
01:25:33,955 --> 01:25:36,954
<i>Halt!</i>

1329
01:25:36,955 --> 01:25:37,954
Ready!

1330
